+# Custom-Field Reporting Dashboard — Spec (`/operator/intelligence`)
+
+_Author: Data/BI design pass (read-only). Scope: the flexible custom-field reporting dashboard + report builder that lives in **Intelligence** (`/operator/intelligence`), grounded in the metric registry (`lib/intelligence/`), the firewall (`lib/intelligence/sponsor-safe.ts`, `prisma/sql/sponsor-audience-view.sql`, `tests/unit/sponsor-firewall.test.ts`), `Member.customFields`/`fieldProvenance`, `FieldDefinition`, `SavedReport`, and `lib/member-editable.ts`._
+
+**Hard frame (RESOLVED-IA-1, founder 2026-06-09):** Intelligence is the analysis hub; Members is the operational spine. This surface aggregates and reports across members — it never becomes a second roster. All artifacts here are operator-internal **unless** explicitly projected through the sponsor firewall, which is the load-bearing constraint of the whole spec.
+
+**Locked honored:** tokens-only (no hex), canonical terminology (Member / Guest / Comp Access / Event Access — never "RSVP" in UI; "Registration fields" stays the application form's name), `claude-sonnet-4-20250514` for any AI assist, additive-schema-only / never `prisma db push`, workspace-scoping on every read. Status: **DRAFT — every decision tagged OPEN is the founder's, not inferred.**
+
+---
+
+## 1. The job
+
+The operator has defined custom fields in their own vocabulary (Slice 2 F5 → `FieldDefinition` + `Member.customFields`). Today those values are captured and editable but **never aggregated** — `customFields` appears in zero query paths outside the firewall type (confirmed: only `sponsor-safe.ts` references it). This surface answers: _"across my room, how do my own fields break down — and which slices fit a sponsor?"_ It is a flexible report builder over an arbitrary, operator-defined, JSON-shaped field set.
+
+Three audiences, one query engine, one firewall:
+
+1. **Operator (internal):** any field — firmographic, demographic, custom, computed, and (clearly walled in a separate region) psychographic rollups already on the existing dashboard.
+2. **Sponsor (external deliverable):** firmographic + `FieldDefinition.sponsorVisible` custom fields **only**, with small-cell suppression. Never psychographics, never operator-authored notes/relationships/flags/lists.
+3. **AI agent (MCP):** reads the same registry; inherits the same firewall by construction.
+
+---
+
+## 2. Report model — ad-hoc vs saved (DECISION)
+
+### What exists
+`SavedReport { name, question, metricIds String[], filters Json, createdById, lastRunAt }` already ships, and `POST /api/intelligence/reports` (STAFF-gated) + `GET` (list) already persist/list it. The dashboard already parses **filters from the URL** (`lib/intelligence/filters.ts`) so any composed view is shareable by link. So the substrate for **both** ad-hoc and saved already exists.
+
+### Recommended model: **both, layered (ad-hoc is the default; saved is a promotion)**
+
+- **Ad-hoc is the working surface.** The report builder composes against the live URL filter-state. Every adjustment re-runs immediately, no persistence. This is the existing dashboard behavior — the custom-field builder extends it, it does not replace it.
+- **Saved is an explicit promotion.** "Save report" snapshots `{ name, question, metricIds, filters }` into `SavedReport`. A saved report is a **named, re-runnable composition**, not a frozen result set — it re-executes against current data on open (stamping `lastRunAt`). This is what the schema already encodes.
+
+### What custom-field reporting adds to the model (the gap)
+
+A custom-field report is **not** a fixed `metricId` — the field is operator-defined at runtime. Two ways to fit it into the existing `SavedReport` shape:
+
+- **OPEN-RPT-1 — how a custom-field report is persisted.** Branches:
+  - **(A) Synthetic metric ids (recommended).** Encode a custom-field breakdown as a parametric metric id, e.g. `customfield.breakdown:<stableKey>`, stored in `SavedReport.metricIds`. The registry resolves the `:<stableKey>` suffix at run time against `FieldDefinition`. **Zero schema change** — reuses `metricIds String[]` exactly as-is. Cost: a parsing convention in the registry.
+  - **(B) New `reportSpec Json` column on `SavedReport`.** A richer, explicit `{ dimension, measure, breakdownBy, segment }` document. Cleaner for multi-dimension reports; **additive schema change** (one nullable column, follows the additive migration path). Cost: a migration + a second persistence shape alongside `metricIds`.
+  - Recommendation: **(A) for v1** (no migration, ships on the existing route), reserve **(B)** for when reports need >1 dimension or a saved chart-type. Flag for founder.
+
+- **OPEN-RPT-2 — saved-report result semantics.** Re-run live (recommended — a report is a question, data moves) **vs** snapshot the computed numbers (needed only if reports back a point-in-time sponsor deliverable that must not drift). Recommend **re-run live** for the dashboard; the **sponsor deliverable** pipeline (`brief-assemble`/`recap-assemble`) already snapshots separately, so the dashboard need not.
+
+- **OPEN-RPT-3 — who can save / share.** `POST /reports` is STAFF-gated today; `GET` is open to any resolved member (read). Confirm: saved reports are **workspace-shared** (every operator sees the workspace's saved reports) vs **per-author private**. Schema has `createdById` but no privacy flag — workspace-shared is the zero-change default. Recommend workspace-shared.
+
+---
+
+## 3. Aggregation / query approach over the `customFields` JSON column
+
+### 3.1 The shape
+`Member.customFields Json?` is a flat object keyed by `FieldDefinition.stableKey` (e.g. `{ "neighborhood": "Tarrytown", "membership_tier": "Charter", "referral_source": "Chloe" }`). `FieldDefinition` carries `{ stableKey, name, type, section, sponsorVisible, options[], isActive }`. The reportable universe of a field = **its `FieldDefinition` row** (drives label, type, whether it's a select with known `options`, and the firewall flag).
+
+### 3.2 Query strategy (DECISION) — **OPEN-QRY-1**
+
+Postgres `jsonb` supports both indexed key-extraction (`->>`) and `GROUP BY` on extracted keys. Two viable engines:
+
+- **(A) SQL `GROUP BY` on the JSON key via `$queryRaw` (recommended for breakdowns).**
+  ```sql
+  SELECT m."customFields"->>'<stableKey>' AS bucket, COUNT(*) AS n
+  FROM "Member" m
+  WHERE m."workspaceId" = $1
+    AND m."mergedIntoId" IS NULL            -- never double-count merged dupes
+    AND m."customFields" ? '<stableKey>'    -- key present
+  GROUP BY 1 ORDER BY n DESC;
+  ```
+  `stableKey` is **never** user-typed into SQL — it is validated against an existing `FieldDefinition.stableKey` for the workspace (allow-list), and `slugifyFieldKey` guarantees `[a-z0-9_]` only. The value goes through a parameter; the key is interpolated only after the allow-list check. This is the only safe interpolation and it MUST be gated on a `FieldDefinition` lookup, not raw input. Counts compute in the DB; cheap; scales.
+
+- **(B) Load-and-reduce in code.** Select `customFields` for the workspace, reduce in TypeScript. Simpler, no raw SQL, mirrors how `metrics.ts` already reduces RSVP rows in code. Cost: pulls every member's JSON into the app; fine at NBC's scale (hundreds–low-thousands), wrong at SaaS scale.
+
+- Recommendation: **(A)** for the operator dashboard (set-based, indexable later with a GIN index on `customFields` via the additive SQL path — same out-of-band class as `Asset_searchVector_idx`, never `db push`); **(B)** acceptable as a v1 shortcut if raw SQL is unwanted. **Flag — OPEN-QRY-1.**
+
+### 3.3 Fit into the metric registry (recommended — reuse, don't fork)
+Custom-field reporting should be a **registry metric family**, not a parallel system. The registry already gives workspace-scope enforcement (`registerMetric` refuses a query that never references `workspaceId`), caching by `refresh` TTL, drill-down, and MCP exposure — all for free.
+
+- A **parametric breakdown metric**: `customfield.breakdown` resolves `:<stableKey>` from context, looks up the `FieldDefinition`, runs the §3.2 query, returns a `Breakdown` (existing `MetricResult` shape → `horizontal-bar`/`donut` viz). `resultType: 'breakdown'`.
+- A **cross-tab matrix metric**: `customfield.crosstab` (field A × field B, or field × access tier / archetype-bucket-internal-only) → existing `Matrix` result shape → `heatmap`/`table` viz.
+- A **coverage/fill-rate metric**: `customfield.coverage` — % of members with the field set, broken down by `fieldProvenance` source (self_reported vs operator_entered vs verified_enrichment vs ai_inferred). Answers "how trustworthy is this field?" `resultType: 'breakdown'`.
+
+These three plus the existing fixed metrics are the whole catalog. **Adding a custom field never requires a code change** — the parametric metric resolves any active `FieldDefinition` at run time. This is the design's core property and it matches the registry's stated contract ("Adding a metric must never require a UI change").
+
+### 3.4 Provenance-aware aggregation
+`fieldProvenance[key] = { value, source, confidence, syncedAt }`. Reports SHOULD let the operator filter/segment by source (e.g. "only `verified_enrichment` industries"), and the **sponsor projection MUST** (see §5) — sponsor aggregates count only `self_reported` + `verified_enrichment`, never `ai_inferred` or `operator_entered`-only inferences. `ProvenanceSource` (`sponsor-safe.ts`) is the single source-of-truth union; the report layer reads it, never re-defines it.
+
+---
+
+## 4. Dashboard + report-builder UX
+
+### 4.1 IA — where it sits
+`/operator/intelligence` is the hub. The custom-field report builder is a **tab/section** within it (`IntelligenceTabs` already exists), alongside the current pipeline/community/engagement tabs and the firewalled Sponsor sub-route (`/operator/intelligence/sponsor`). It deep-links to **Field setup** (Settings → member-fields) so the operator can define a field then report on it without leaving the loop, and deep-links **back to Members** for drill-down (a breakdown cell → the matching roster slice).
+
+```
+/operator/intelligence
+├── (existing) Pipeline / Community / Engagement / Taste tabs ...... internal, unchanged
+├── Reports (NEW) ................................................... the custom-field builder
+│     ├── Build panel (dimension + measure + filters)
+│     ├── Result canvas (chart + table + insight line)
+│     ├── Save report → SavedReport
+│     ├── Saved reports list (GET /reports)
+│     └── drill-down cell → Members roster slice  /  → Settings field setup
+└── Sponsor (existing) ............................................. FIREWALLED sub-route
+```
+
+### 4.2 Report builder — the three controls
+A breadboard, not a BI cockpit. Three controls answer 90% of questions:
+
+1. **Dimension (break down by):** a dropdown of reportable fields = active `FieldDefinition`s (custom) **+** the editable firmographic columns (`EDITABLE_MEMBER_COLUMNS` from `lib/member-editable.ts`: industry, jobFunction, seniority, companySize, companyName, city, country, ageRange, …). **Excluded from the picker by construction:** `RESERVED_FIELD_KEYS` (psychographic — never offered) and identity/computed `READONLY_MEMBER_KEYS` that make no sense as a dimension. The picker is generated from `lib/member-editable.ts` + `FieldDefinition`, so it can never offer a firewalled key.
+2. **Measure:** `Count of members` (default) · `% of total` · later `Coverage / fill-rate`. v1 is count + percent; keep it small.
+3. **Filters/segment:** the existing `IntelligenceFilterState` (date range, tier, source, neighborhood, compare) **+** a custom-field equals/in filter (`field = value`). Filters stay in the URL (shareable). Compare-period reuses the existing `compare: previous | year-ago`.
+
+Optional second dimension → cross-tab (matrix). Flagged behind OPEN-RPT-1(B) for persistence.
+
+### 4.3 States (designed, per the Form spec vocabulary)
+- **Empty (no custom fields defined yet):** `No custom fields yet.` + link `Set up member fields` (→ Settings). The builder still offers firmographic dimensions so it is never wholly empty.
+- **Empty (field defined, no values captured):** `No members have a value for "{field}" yet.`
+- **Suppressed-only result (sponsor scope):** if every cell is below `MIN_CELL`, show `Not enough members to report without identifying individuals.` (never render a 1–4 person cell in sponsor scope).
+- **Loading:** server-rendered tiles; skeleton bars (2-line, `--muted`) for any async metric, per the Form spec — no spinners.
+- **Error:** `Could not run this report.` (and the catch block logs, per the Absolute Rule).
+
+### 4.4 Copy (tokens of language, locked terminology honored)
+- Tab: `Reports`. Builder title: `Build a report`.
+- Controls: `Break down by` · `Measure` · `Filter`.
+- Measures: `Members` · `Share of members`.
+- Save: `Save report` · busy `Saving…` · saved toast `"{name}" saved`.
+- Saved list: `Saved reports`, row = name + `question` + `Last run {relative}`.
+- Sponsor toggle (see §5): `Sponsor-safe view` with helper `Firmographic fields only. Psychographics and notes are never shown.`
+- Drill-down: `View these members` (→ Members roster slice) — Member/Guest/Comp Access language only.
+
+### 4.5 Permissions
+- **View reports / run ad-hoc:** any resolved member (read), matching the existing open-GET posture.
+- **Save report:** STAFF (existing `POST /reports` gate). Unchanged.
+- **Toggle sponsor-safe view / generate a sponsor deliverable:** the existing sponsor sub-route is already in the firewalled region; the builder's sponsor-safe toggle simply re-runs through the sponsor projection. No new gate, but the **firewall** (not RBAC) is what makes it safe.
+
+---
+
+## 5. Firewall enforcement at the query layer (the load-bearing section)
+
+The firewall is **structural, not a UI toggle**. The custom-field builder MUST inherit it at the query layer so that no composition — ad-hoc, saved, or AI-driven — can ever emit psychographic or operator-authored data to a sponsor. Enforcement is layered (defense in depth), every layer already has precedent in the repo:
+
+### Layer 1 — physical table boundary (exists)
+Psychographics live in `MemberPsychographics`, a **separate table**. The sponsor view (`prisma/sql/sponsor-audience-view.sql`) has **no JOIN** and an **explicit column list** — it physically cannot reach archetype/interests/tasteSignals. The custom-field builder, when in sponsor scope, MUST read **from `sponsor_audience_member`, not `Member`.** That single substitution carries the firewall for free: the view exposes only `industry, jobFunction, seniority, companySize, companyName, companyDomain, linkedinUrl, city, country, ageRange, customFields, fieldProvenance` — and only for `status = 'APPROVED' AND mergedIntoId IS NULL`.
+
+### Layer 2 — `customFields` sub-filtering by `sponsorVisible` (the new enforcement this spec adds)
+The view passes `customFields` **whole** (it cannot know which keys are sponsor-visible — that's the reader's job, per the view's own comment). So the sponsor-scope reader MUST, after reading the view:
+1. Load the workspace's `FieldDefinition` rows where `sponsorVisible = true AND isActive = true` → an **allow-set of stableKeys**.
+2. Project each member's `customFields` down to **only** those keys (drop everything else).
+3. Restrict the **dimension picker in sponsor scope** to that same allow-set + the firmographic columns — an operator literally cannot select a non-sponsor-visible field to break down on when the sponsor-safe view is on.
+
+This is the rule the existing `toSponsorAudienceMember` comment already names ("already filtered to `FieldDefinition.sponsorVisible`") but which has no aggregation consumer yet — **this spec is that consumer**, and it MUST perform the filter, not assume it.
+
+### Layer 3 — type boundary (exists, must be used)
+Every sponsor-scope value flows through `SponsorAudienceMember` (`lib/intelligence/sponsor-safe.ts`). The compile-time `_SponsorSafe` assertion fails the build if a psychographic key is ever added to that shape. The custom-field reader's sponsor path MUST type its rows as `SponsorAudienceMember` and pass through `toSponsorAudienceMember`, so any attempt to carry archetype/interests/tasteSignals is a **compile error**.
+
+### Layer 4 — provenance restriction (sponsor scope)
+Sponsor aggregates count only `self_reported` + `verified_enrichment` provenance (never `ai_inferred`, never operator-only inference) — per the view comment and `ProvenanceSource`. The reader reads `fieldProvenance[key].source` and excludes the rest before counting.
+
+### Layer 5 — small-cell suppression (exists, must be applied)
+Reuse `MIN_CELL = 5` and `toDistribution` from `lib/intelligence/metrics.ts`: any sponsor-facing breakdown cell < 5 members rolls into a suppressed "Other" bucket. A sponsor can never see a slice small enough to re-identify a person. Operator-scope reports do **not** suppress (internal).
+
+### Layer 6 — the test gate (exists; extend the registry, not the gate)
+`tests/unit/sponsor-firewall.test.ts` is the gate. It (a) source-scans the `SPONSOR_FACING` file list for psychographic read tokens (`MemberPsychographics|archetypeScores|archetypeAverages|tasteSignals|psychographics`), (b) asserts the type boundary exports, and (c) asserts the view is JOIN-free / explicit-columns / dedup+APPROVED. **Implication for this spec (OPEN-FW-1):** if the sponsor-scope custom-field reader is a new file/module that assembles a sponsor deliverable, it MUST be **added to the `SPONSOR_FACING` array** so the source-scan covers it. The spec flags this as a required test change — the gate only protects files it lists. The operator-scope reader is internal and stays off the list.
+
+### The single rule
+> **Operator scope reads `Member` (+ may read `MemberPsychographics` for the existing internal psychographic tiles). Sponsor scope reads `sponsor_audience_member`, filters `customFields` to `sponsorVisible` keys, restricts provenance, types as `SponsorAudienceMember`, suppresses sub-`MIN_CELL` cells.** The two code paths never share a query. Scope is a hard branch, chosen server-side, never a client flag the client can flip to widen access.
+
+- **OPEN-FW-2 — is the dashboard's sponsor-safe toggle ever a real sponsor deliverable, or only an operator preview of one?** If it can export/share (like `/assets/[token]`), it is a SPONSOR_FACING surface and inherits the full §5 stack + the test-list addition. If it is only an operator-side "preview what a sponsor would see," it still must use the sponsor path (so the preview is honest) but the export gating differs. Recommend: preview-only in the dashboard; real deliverables stay in the existing `/sponsor` brief/recap pipeline. **Founder decides.**
+
+---
+
+## 6. Chart types (mapped to existing `MetricViz`)
+
+Reuse the registry's `MetricViz` union (`number | sparkline | line | bar | horizontal-bar | donut | heatmap | table | funnel`) and the existing `charts.tsx`. No new chart library.
+
+| Report intent | Result shape | Viz | Notes |
+|---|---|---|---|
+| Single custom-field breakdown | `Breakdown` | `horizontal-bar` (default) or `donut` | Bar for many buckets, donut for ≤5; sponsor scope suppresses <5 cells |
+| Coverage / fill-rate by provenance | `Breakdown` | `horizontal-bar` | source = self/operator/verified/ai; trust signal |
+| Field A × Field B (or × tier) | `Matrix` | `heatmap` or `table` | cross-tab; behind OPEN-RPT-1(B) for save |
+| Trend of a field's bucket over time | `TimeSeries` | `line` | needs a date axis — set/captured date; OPEN-CHT-1 below |
+| Headline count (members with field set) | scalar | `number` + `sparkline` | tile at top of report |
+| Roster-style raw list (drill-down) | `RecordList` | `table` | the "View these members" expansion; firmographic columns only in sponsor scope |
+
+- **OPEN-CHT-1 — time-series dimension for custom fields.** `customFields` has no per-value timestamp except `fieldProvenance[key].syncedAt`. A "trend" report needs a date to bucket on — use `syncedAt` (when the field was last set, approximate) vs `Member.createdAt` (when the person entered) vs no time-series for custom fields in v1. Recommend **no custom-field time-series in v1** (firmographic/pipeline trends already exist on the main dashboard); flag for founder.
+- **OPEN-CHT-2 — default chart per field type.** Auto-pick from `FieldDefinition.type`: `select`/`enum` (known `options[]`) → donut/bar; free-text → bar of top-N + "Other"; number → histogram (no histogram viz exists today — would fall back to bucketed bar). Recommend auto-default with a manual override; flag whether a histogram viz is worth adding (it is not in v1).
+
+---
+
+## 7. Schema impact
+
+| Need | Schema change? | Path |
+|---|---|---|
+| Save custom-field reports via synthetic metric ids (OPEN-RPT-1 A) | **NO** | Reuses `SavedReport.metricIds String[]` as-is |
+| Richer report spec (OPEN-RPT-1 B) | **YES, additive** | One nullable `reportSpec Json` column; additive migration path (edit schema → `prisma generate` → `migrate diff --script`, refuse any DROP/ALTER/RENAME → `db execute --file`); never `db push`; never touch `Asset_searchVector_idx` |
+| Indexed JSON aggregation at scale (OPEN-QRY-1 A) | **Optional, additive, out-of-band** | A GIN index on `Member.customFields`, same class as `Asset_searchVector_idx` / the sponsor view — hand-applied SQL, NOT in `schema.prisma`, never `db push`. Not needed at NBC scale; flag for SaaS scale |
+| Everything else (read-only aggregation) | **NO** | Pure query work over existing columns + the existing view |
+
+The recommended v1 (RPT-1 A + QRY-1 A or B) is **zero schema change** — it ships on the existing `SavedReport` model and `/api/intelligence/reports` route.
+
+---
+
+## 8. Consolidated open decisions (founder decides — do not infer)
+
+| ID | Decision | Recommendation |
+|----|----------|----------------|
+| **OPEN-RPT-1** | How a custom-field report persists: (A) synthetic metric ids in `metricIds` vs (B) new `reportSpec Json` column | (A) for v1 — zero schema change |
+| **OPEN-RPT-2** | Saved-report semantics: re-run live vs snapshot numbers | Re-run live (dashboard); deliverables snapshot in the existing sponsor pipeline |
+| **OPEN-RPT-3** | Saved reports workspace-shared vs per-author private | Workspace-shared (zero-change default) |
+| **OPEN-QRY-1** | Aggregation engine: (A) SQL `GROUP BY` on `jsonb` (allow-listed key) vs (B) load-and-reduce in code | (A) for set-based scale; (B) acceptable v1 shortcut |
+| **OPEN-FW-1** | Add the sponsor-scope custom-field reader module to `tests/unit/sponsor-firewall.test.ts` `SPONSOR_FACING` array | **Required** if it assembles any sponsor-facing output — flag as a test change |
+| **OPEN-FW-2** | Is the dashboard sponsor-safe view a real exportable deliverable or an operator preview? | Preview-only in dashboard; real deliverables stay in `/sponsor` pipeline |
+| **OPEN-CHT-1** | Time-series dimension for custom fields (`syncedAt` vs `createdAt` vs none) | None in v1 |
+| **OPEN-CHT-2** | Auto default chart per `FieldDefinition.type` + whether to add a histogram viz | Auto-default with override; no histogram in v1 |
+| **OPEN-IA-2** (carried) | Record sectioning once reporting cards land on the record (from UX spec) | Tabs once >4 cards (carried, not re-decided here) |
+
+---
+
+## 9. Locked constraints honored
+
+- **Firewall is the gate.** No operator-authored or psychographic data ever enters a sponsor report; the sponsor path reads the view, filters to `sponsorVisible`, restricts provenance, types as `SponsorAudienceMember`, suppresses sub-`MIN_CELL` cells; `sponsor-firewall.test.ts` stays the gate and is extended (OPEN-FW-1) to cover any new sponsor-facing reader.
+- **Tokens only, no hex** — all charts/tiles/builder controls use existing semantic tokens + `charts.tsx`.
+- **Locked terminology** — Member / Guest / Comp Access / Event Access (never "RSVP" in UI); "Registration fields" remains the application-form name; no raw enum values surfaced.
+- **AI model** — any AI report-narration uses `claude-sonnet-4-20250514` (no new model). (No AI is required for v1 of this surface.)
+- **Additive schema only, never `prisma db push`** — recommended v1 is zero-schema; any optional column/index follows the additive `db execute` path and never touches `Asset_searchVector_idx`.
+- **Workspace scoping** — every query references `workspaceId`; the registry refuses any metric that doesn't.
+- **Reuse over fork** — custom-field reporting is a registry metric family, not a parallel engine; it inherits scope-enforcement, caching, drill-down, and MCP exposure from `lib/intelligence/registry.ts`.
+
+## 10. Out of scope
+
+- Editing fields / defining `FieldDefinition`s (that is Slice 2 F5 + Settings → member-fields; this surface only **reports** on them and deep-links to setup).
+- The existing internal psychographic/taste tiles on `/operator/intelligence` (unchanged; they stay in the operator-only region).
+- The `/sponsor` brief/recap deliverable pipeline (unchanged; the dashboard's sponsor-safe view is a preview of, not a replacement for, it).
+- Any migration execution (planning only; the additive paths are specified, not run).
+- Relationships/Lists/Act reporting (those tables don't exist yet per `OPERATOR-CRM-ROADMAP.md`; when they do, they are operator-internal and never enter the sponsor projection).
