+# Import + Identity-Unification — Scope (FILE-ONLY)
+
+| Field | Value |
+|---|---|
+| **Type** | Audit / scope doc (not a stage `CONTEXT.md`) |
+| **Last updated** | 2026-06-10 |
+| **Owner** | Adam |
+| **State** | 🟡 Scoping — no code, no schema, no DB writes in this pass |
+| **Home stage** | Feeds `_context/16-member-intelligence/` (Operator CRM + the Gravity Ledger). This workstream is the **front door** that populates the nodes that stage reasons over. |
+| **Purpose** | Scope how patron data from **Posh, Luma, and ActiveCampaign (Chloe's)** lands in NoBC OS as **one canonical patron per real human**. |
+
+> This is a planning artifact. It proposes; it does not build. Every schema line here is a *proposal* to be reviewed against the file-only additive workflow before anything touches the DB. Open decisions are flagged inline and collected in §12 — **nothing in §12 is assumed resolved.**
+
+---
+
+## 1. Thesis — the hard 80% is identity, and we are not importing a relationship graph
+
+Extraction is the easy 20%. Three CSV/API pulls is a week of adapter plumbing. The load-bearing 80% is **identity resolution**: the same human is `chloe@gmail.com` in ActiveCampaign, `chloe.r@work.com` on a Posh order, and `@chloerose` with a different email on Luma. If those land as three rows, the platform believes there are three patrons.
+
+Why this is load-bearing and not cosmetic: the sphere-of-influence engine (`lib/member-connections.ts`, the Gravity Ledger) measures a person's pull through **provable edges** — who they *brought* (`RSVP.plusOneOfMemberId`), who they *referred* (`Member.referredByMemberId`), and the **CAPTURED dollars** those people spent. Every edge and every dollar hangs off a `memberId`. Fragmented identity splits one person's real gravity across phantom nodes: the host who actually drives your room shows up as three half-weight ghosts, none of which crosses the "stuck" or revenue threshold. **Unified identity is the precondition for the gravity graph being true.** This is the single reason to do the hard part properly.
+
+**What import can and cannot seed (state this loudly to avoid a false promise):**
+
+- ✅ Import seeds **nodes** — people, their contact identities, and a thin backfill of historical attendance ("this person was at these past events").
+- ❌ Import does **not** seed **edges**. Posh/Luma/AC exports do not reliably carry *who-brought-whom* or trustworthy *who-checked-in-next-to-whom*. The Gravity Ledger's `brought` / `referred` / `proximity` primitives are **NoBC-native** — they are minted by NoBC's own plus-one capture, referral spine, and door check-ins, and they **compound forward** from the moment a patron is unified. We import the *roster*; the *relationship graph* is grown here, not imported.
+
+The Gravity Ledger data contract already encodes this discipline (`_context/16-member-intelligence/UI-GRAVITY-LEDGER.md` §3, the "met" law): co-presence is not acquaintance; only `brought`, `referred`, `checked in` are sayable. Import must respect that — it may not manufacture a "knows" edge out of "both attended Posh event X."
+
+---
+
+## 2. What already exists (do not rebuild — extend)
+
+This workstream is mostly **wiring three adapters into machinery that already shipped.** Inventory of the load-bearing pieces, verified in-repo (code-read 2026-06-10):
+
+| Asset | File | What it already does |
+|---|---|---|
+| **Single birth path** | `lib/member-identity.ts` → `resolveMember()` | Find-or-create keyed on `(workspaceId, normalized email)`. Mints synthetic `clerkUserId` (`guest:<email>`) when there is no Clerk account, always `status=GUEST`, always a `memberQrCode`, **follows `mergedIntoId`** to the canonical row. Takes a `source` provenance string. **Every import row should route through this — not raw `member.create`.** |
+| **Soft-merge engine** | `lib/member-merge.ts` | `normEmail` / `normPhone` (strips formatting + leading US `1`) / `normInstagram` (strips `@`, profile-URL, query string). `findMergeCandidates()` → `email_exact` (auto), `phone` + `instagram` (operator-confirm only, `autoMergeable: false`). `executeMerge()` re-points `memberId` only (never `eventId`), guards the `@@unique([workspaceId, eventId, memberId])` RSVP collision by archiving dupes (`status=DECLINED`, `ticketStatus='merged_duplicate'`), tombstones the loser via `mergedIntoId`/`mergedAt`, writes an `auditEvent`. `autoMergeExactEmailDuplicates()` auto-merges exact-email only. |
+| **Canonical model + provenance** | `prisma/schema.prisma` → `Member` | `mergedIntoId`/`mergedAt` + self-relation `mergedInto`/`mergedFrom`; `customFields Json?`; `fieldProvenance Json?` (per-field `{value, source, confidence, syncedAt}`); `instagram`, `linkedinUrl`, `phone`, `companyDomain`, `referredByMemberId`, `networkCapitalScore`. Uniques: `(workspaceId, clerkUserId)`, `(workspaceId, email)`. Indexes incl. `(workspaceId, phone)`. |
+| **Per-field provenance write-path** | `lib/member-provenance.ts` | `PROVENANCE_SOURCES` union (live, code-verified): `self_reported \| operator_entered \| ai_inferred \| verified_enrichment \| producer`. Pure `mergeProvenance()` that stamps `fieldProvenance[key] = {value, source, confidence, syncedAt}` alongside `customFields[key]`. **`posh`, `luma`, `activecampaign` are NOT yet in this union — adding them is a code change, not a schema change.** |
+| **External-source idempotency precedent** | `prisma/schema.prisma` → `Tag` | `externalSource TagSource @default(manual)` + `externalId String?` + `@@unique([workspaceId, externalSource, externalId])`. **`TagSource` already includes `activecampaign`.** This is the exact pattern to mirror for member source identities — and AC tag/segment import has a ready home here. |
+| **Gravity contract** | `_context/16-member-intelligence/UI-GRAVITY-LEDGER.md` | Defines the provable primitives and the "met" law import must not violate. Engine lives in the not-yet-merged `member-connections` worktree (commit `6ee4d30`). The falsification run (120 members / 6 events) confirmed gravity (`brought`/`referred`/captured dollars) catches 8/8 real connectors; reach (co-attendance) catches 0/8. **Import must not manufacture `brought` edges.** |
+| **Additive migration workflow** | `prisma/sql/additive_*.sql` | Established pattern: `additive_member_merge.sql`, `additive_pr2_dimensions.sql`, `additive_pr2_dimensions.sql`. New tables ship as additive SQL, never `db push`. Binary path: `node node_modules/prisma/build/index.js` (Prisma 7.8.0, `npx` broken). |
+| **Backfill script pattern** | `scripts/backfill-member-firmographics.ts`, `scripts/backfill-referrals.ts` | Established: dry-run default, idempotent, row-rate-limited. Any import backfill script should follow this pattern. |
+
+**Zero Posh/Luma/ActiveCampaign code today.** A full grep of `app/` and `lib/` (2026-06-10) finds no import runner, no adapter, no CSV parser, no Posh/Luma/AC API client. Starting from scratch on the adapter layer.
+
+**The genuine gaps** (what is *not* there and this workstream must add):
+
+1. **No source-identity join table** — `resolveMember` takes a `source` *string* but nothing records *which platform row* a person came from. Without it there is no idempotency key and no provenance for un-merge.
+2. **No `unMerge()` function** — `member-merge.ts` says a merge is "reversible by nulling the pointer," but there is no function that nulls it *and* un-re-points the archived/re-pointed history. Reversibility is currently a claim, not a code path.
+3. **No persisted rejection memory** — `findMergeCandidates` computes on the fly; a "these two are NOT the same person" decision is not stored, so any re-import re-floods the queue with already-rejected pairs (breaks idempotent re-import of the *review* surface).
+4. **`posh`/`luma`/`activecampaign` not in `PROVENANCE_SOURCES`** — additive code change required before any import can stamp source provenance on field values.
+5. **No import runner / batch ledger / review UI.**
+
+---
+
+## 3. Per-source capability matrix (CAN / CANNOT)
+
+> ⚠️ **Pending verification (Open Decision §12.1).** Exact export columns vary by plan tier and by export *method* (dashboard CSV vs API). The matrix below is the **expected** shape and must be locked against **one real sample export per source** before any adapter field-map is frozen. Do not treat a ✅ as confirmed until a sample is in hand.
+
+| Capability | Posh | Luma | ActiveCampaign (Chloe's) |
+|---|---|---|---|
+| Person name | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |
+| Email (identity key) | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ (primary key) |
+| Phone | ⚠️ sometimes (checkout) | ⚠️ sometimes (reg question) | ✅ often (contact field) |
+| Instagram handle | ❌ not in standard export | ❌ unless a custom reg question | ⚠️ only if a custom field exists |
+| **Which past events attended** | ✅ per-event attendee list | ✅ per-event guest list | ❌ (marketing CRM, no events) |
+| Registration / order timestamp | ✅ | ✅ | N/A (subscribe date only) |
+| **Check-in timestamp** | ⚠️ unreliable in export | ⚠️ sometimes (Luma check-in) | ❌ |
+| Purchase amount (past) | ✅ paid events | ⚠️ paid events only | ❌ |
+| Tags / segments | ❌ | ⚠️ limited | ✅ rich (→ existing `Tag` + `TagSource.activecampaign`) |
+| Custom fields / reg answers | ⚠️ reg questions | ✅ reg questions | ✅ contact custom fields |
+| Marketing engagement (opens/clicks) | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |
+| **Co-registration (group order)** | ⚠️ buyer known; guests often name-only | ⚠️ "invited by" sometimes | ❌ |
+| **Who-brought-whom (plus-one edge)** | ❌ | ❌ (mostly) | ❌ |
+| Stable per-row external ID | ⚠️ order/ticket id if present | ✅ guest/event id (API) | ✅ contact id |
+
+**Reading of the matrix:**
+
+- **ActiveCampaign is the identity spine.** Richest contact data (email + phone + tags + custom fields), strongest stable IDs, but **zero event history**. It tells you *who the people are*.
+- **Posh + Luma are the attendance spine.** They tell you *who showed up where* (nodes + thin historical attendance), but carry weak phone/IG and **no reliable relationship edges**.
+- **No source delivers a relationship graph.** Group-order "co-registration" is the closest signal, and it is buyer→guest-name, not a verified person-to-person edge. Treat any imported co-registration as, at most, a *weak, operator-reviewable* hint — never as a `brought` edge that feeds gravity. (Open Decision §12.6.)
+- **Historical check-ins, where present, are NoBC-native-equivalent** and may seed the "stuck"/attendance signal — but their export fidelity is the weakest column in the table, so the Gravity Ledger's check-in counts will be **predominantly forward-accumulated**, not backfilled. Set that expectation explicitly.
+
+---
+
+## 4. Matching strategy
+
+Two tiers, mirroring the engine that already exists. Reuse `lib/member-merge.ts` normalizers verbatim — do not write new ones.
+
+### 4.1 Deterministic tier → certainty only
+
+- **Exact normalized email** (`normEmail`) → **silent auto-merge / auto-resolve.** This is what `resolveMember` (find-or-create on `(workspaceId, email)`) and `autoMergeExactEmailDuplicates` already do. An import row whose email matches an existing canonical member attaches to that member; no human in the loop.
+- **Exact normalized phone / exact normalized Instagram** → **high-confidence, but NOT silent.** The shipped engine deliberately marks these `autoMergeable: false` (a shared family phone, a recycled handle, a partner's number are *not* certain identity). 
+  - ⚠️ **Tension with the brief, flagged not resolved (Open Decision §12.2):** the workstream brief lists "email/phone/Instagram, normalized → auto-merge the certain." The shipped code treats only email as certain. **Recommendation:** keep email as the only silent auto-merge; surface phone-exact and IG-exact in the review queue **pre-selected / one-click confirm** rather than auto-applied. This honors "never auto-merge ambiguous" and does not regress the deliberate stance in `member-merge.ts`. Adam decides.
+
+### 4.2 Fuzzy tier → human-review queue, never auto
+
+- **Name similarity** (token-sorted, case/diacritic-normalized; e.g. high Levenshtein/Jaro on `first last`) → **always the review queue, never auto-merge**, and only worth surfacing when a **corroborating weak signal** co-occurs (same city, same source event, overlapping phone area) to keep the queue from drowning in coincidental name collisions.
+- **Never auto-merge ambiguous.** Ambiguity defaults to "leave as two people" — a false split is recoverable (merge later); a false merge corrupts the gravity graph and is only recoverable if un-merge exists (§5.3).
+
+### 4.3 Normalization limits to flag
+
+`normPhone` strips formatting and a leading US `1` only — it is **not** full E.164 / libphonenumber. International numbers and extension formats may not normalize to equality. (Open Decision §12.3 — adopt libphonenumber or accept US-centric matching.)
+
+### 4.4 Provenance source registration (code change, not schema)
+
+`lib/member-provenance.ts::PROVENANCE_SOURCES` is a `z.enum` — a hard union, not a freeform string. **`posh`, `luma`, and `activecampaign` must be added to this union before any import can stamp provenance on field values.** This is one file, one array, additive. But it is a decision: once in the enum, these values persist in the DB across JSON blobs. (Open Decision §12.11.) The alternative is a new `'import'` source key that all three share — loses per-platform attribution but avoids the enum sprawl.
+
+---
+
+## 5. Canonical patron, provenance, and reversible un-merge
+
+### 5.1 Canonical record = the surviving `Member` row
+
+No new "canonical person" entity. The existing soft-merge model is correct: duplicates point at the survivor via `mergedIntoId`; reads resolve through `followMergedInto`. Import adds *nodes and provenance*, not a parallel identity model.
+
+### 5.2 Source provenance (additive table — never destroy source rows)
+
+A person can come from **many** sources, so provenance is one-to-many → a join table, not Member columns:
+
+```
+// PROPOSED — additive only, file-only workflow (§6). Names/shape are a proposal.
+model MemberSourceIdentity {
+  id              String   @id @default(cuid())
+  workspaceId     String                     // workspace-scoped, indexed, checked on every read
+  memberId        String                     // current canonical owner (re-points on merge)
+  originalMemberId String                    // the member it was FIRST imported into — set once, never changed (enables un-merge restore)
+  source          String                     // 'posh' | 'luma' | 'activecampaign' (enum candidate — §12.4)
+  sourceRecordId  String                     // stable per-row id, or a deterministic hash when absent (§12.5)
+  sourceEmail     String?
+  sourceName      String?
+  rawPayload      Json?                       // verbatim imported row — operator-internal, NEVER sponsor-facing
+  importBatchId   String
+  importedAt      DateTime @default(now())
+
+  @@unique([workspaceId, source, sourceRecordId])   // ← THE idempotency key
+  @@index([workspaceId, memberId])
+  @@index([workspaceId, source])
+}
+```
+
+- `rawPayload` makes the original source data **permanently recoverable** — we satisfy "never destroy source rows" by never overwriting it. Edits/merges change `Member`, never the stored source row.
+- `originalMemberId` is the un-merge anchor: on un-merge, source identities return to the member they were born into.
+- AC **tags/segments** do not go here — they route to the existing `Tag` model with `externalSource: activecampaign` + `externalId` (precedent already in schema).
+
+### 5.3 Reversible un-merge (the real gap)
+
+Today's `executeMerge` is reversible at the *pointer* level (null `mergedIntoId`) but it also **archived** colliding Event Access rows and **re-pointed** the rest without recording which were which — so a naive pointer-null does **not** restore the pre-merge state. To make un-merge trustworthy:
+
+```
+// PROPOSED — additive only. Records exactly what a merge changed, so it can be reversed.
+model MemberMergeEvent {
+  id               String   @id @default(cuid())
+  workspaceId      String
+  canonicalId      String
+  loserId          String
+  repointedRsvpIds String[]                  // restore memberId=loserId on un-merge
+  archivedRsvpIds  String[]                  // restore status/ticketStatus on un-merge
+  repointed        Json                       // tickets/waitlist/engagement/surveys/referrals counts + ids
+  matchType        String                     // 'email_exact' | 'phone' | 'instagram' | 'name_fuzzy'
+  actorId          String
+  reason           String?
+  mergedAt         DateTime @default(now())
+  unmergedAt       DateTime?
+
+  @@index([workspaceId, canonicalId])
+  @@index([workspaceId, loserId])
+}
+```
+
+- New code: an `unMerge(mergeEventId)` that reverses `repointedRsvpIds` / `archivedRsvpIds`, nulls `mergedIntoId`/`mergedAt`, stamps `unmergedAt`, writes an audit event.
+- ⚠️ **Open Decision §12.7 — how reversible must un-merge be?** Node-level (null the pointer; history stays on canonical) is cheap but lossy. Full restoration (the model above) is correct but heavier. The brief says "reversible un-merge — never destroy source rows"; source rows are never destroyed either way (§5.2), but *history restoration* fidelity is a real choice.
+
+---
+
+## 6. Idempotent re-import
+
+Re-running any import must converge, never duplicate:
+
+1. **Person idempotency** — every row routes through `resolveMember` (email find-or-create) → unchanged rows resolve to the same canonical member, zero new people.
+2. **Source-row idempotency** — `MemberSourceIdentity @@unique([workspaceId, source, sourceRecordId])` upserts: a re-imported row updates its existing identity, never inserts a twin.
+3. **Review idempotency** — persisted rejection state (a `status` on the candidate queue, §7) means a re-import does **not** re-surface a pair an operator already said "not the same person" to.
+4. **Stable key when the source lacks one** (Open Decision §12.5) — when an export has no durable per-row id, derive `sourceRecordId = hash(source + normalizedEmail [+ eventId])`. Deterministic → idempotent. Must be chosen per source against the real sample (§12.1).
+5. **Batch ledger** for observability + audit:
+
+```
+// PROPOSED — additive only.
+model ImportBatch {
+  id            String   @id @default(cuid())
+  workspaceId   String
+  source        String
+  method        String                        // 'csv' | 'api'
+  fileName      String?
+  rowCount      Int
+  createdCount  Int                            // new people
+  matchedCount  Int                            // resolved to existing
+  queuedCount   Int                            // sent to review
+  status        String                         // 'processing' | 'complete' | 'failed'
+  createdBy     String
+  createdAt     DateTime @default(now())
+
+  @@index([workspaceId, source])
+}
+```
+
+A clean re-run of the same export shows `createdCount: 0` — the litmus test for idempotency.
+
+---
+
+## 7. Human-review merge queue — UX
+
+A new operator surface (proposed: `/operator/members/review` or a tab beside `/operator/members/connectors`, where merge/connection surfaces already live). Read-gated via `requireRolePage`; merges are STAFF+ writes via `requireRole`. **Semantic tokens only (no hex). Copy uses "Event Access," never "RSVP."**
+
+**Persisted candidate model** (so review survives sessions and rejections stick):
+
+```
+// PROPOSED — additive only.
+model MemberMatchCandidate {
+  id          String   @id @default(cuid())
+  workspaceId String
+  memberAId   String
+  memberBId   String
+  matchType   String                           // 'phone' | 'instagram' | 'name_fuzzy'
+  score       Float?                            // fuzzy confidence; null for exact-signal
+  evidence    Json                              // the provable receipt: "same phone 512•••", "name 0.94 + same event"
+  status      String   @default("pending")      // 'pending' | 'merged' | 'rejected'
+  reviewedBy  String?
+  reviewedAt  DateTime?
+  createdAt   DateTime @default(now())
+
+  @@unique([workspaceId, memberAId, memberBId]) // one pair, one row → re-import respects prior decision
+  @@index([workspaceId, status])
+}
+```
+
+**Queue row anatomy** (one pending pair):
+
+- **Two records side-by-side** — name, email, phone, IG, status, **source-provenance chips** ("Posh • Luma" vs "ActiveCampaign").
+- **The evidence, stated as a receipt** — *why* they're a candidate ("Same phone, normalized 512•••1234" / "Name match 0.94 + both at 'Rooftop Social'"). Never "looks like." Mirror the Gravity Ledger's evidence-first discipline.
+- **Actions:** `Merge` (pick survivor — default approved-preferred then older, matching the engine; operator may override) · `Not the same person` (→ `rejected`, persisted) · `Skip`.
+- **Pre-merge transparency:** show what will move — the `executeMerge` result already returns `repointed` counts (Event Access, tickets, waitlist, engagement, surveys, referrals). Surface them before confirm.
+- **Empty / sparse / loading / error** states in the Gravity-Ledger idiom (no fabricated counts; honest zeros).
+
+The deterministic email tier never appears here — it auto-resolves. Only phone/IG (per §12.2) and name-fuzzy reach the queue.
+
+---
+
+## 8. Sponsor firewall, terminology, tokens (non-negotiables carried through)
+
+- **Sponsor firewall.** `MemberSourceIdentity.rawPayload` and the review queue are **operator-internal, never sponsor-facing.** Imported demographic/firmographic values may flow to `customFields`/`fieldProvenance` (already sponsor-classifiable), but **no imported field auto-routes to a sponsor surface** without going through the existing classification — and psychographic data stays in the firewalled `MemberPsychographics` table, never reachable from import-to-sponsor.
+- **Terminology.** "Event Access," never "RSVP," in all UI/copy (the `RSVP` table name stays in code/schema). Imported attendees display as **Guest** (`MemberStatus.GUEST`) until promoted through the normal gate — import **never** mints `APPROVED` (same law `resolveMember` already enforces).
+- **No hex literals.** All review-queue/import UI uses semantic tokens (`bg-primary`, `text-text-primary`, …).
+- **Workspace scoping.** Every proposed table carries `workspaceId`, is indexed on it, and is checked on every query. No cross-tenant read path.
+
+---
+
+## 9. Hard constraints acknowledged (operational)
+
+- **Never `prisma db push`.** All schema deltas here are **additive only** and ship as reviewed SQL under `prisma/sql/additive_*.sql` via `prisma db execute --file …` (the established pattern), after a diff that is refused if it contains any DROP / ALTER TYPE / RENAME.
+- **`npx prisma` is broken in this repo.** Use the local binary directly: `node node_modules/prisma/build/index.js generate` (verified present, Prisma 7.8.0). File-only in this pass — **no generate, no execute, no DB contact happens now.**
+- **Producer shares the Postgres landmine.** Reinforces additive-only; coordinate before anything non-additive (none proposed).
+
+---
+
+## 10. Sizing — S / M / L
+
+### S — "Unify on the spine, prove the loop" (the honest MVP, ~the 80%)
+- **One source first: ActiveCampaign** (richest identity, cleanest stable IDs, no event-history complexity).
+- Additive tables: `MemberSourceIdentity` + `ImportBatch`. (No Member column changes.)
+- One AC adapter → `resolveMember` per row (email find-or-create) → write source identity (idempotent upsert) → AC tags to existing `Tag`/`TagSource.activecampaign`.
+- Deterministic email auto-merge reusing `autoMergeExactEmailDuplicates`.
+- Minimal review queue reusing `findMergeCandidates`/`executeMerge` for phone/IG (compute-on-read; `MemberMatchCandidate` persistence deferred to M).
+- **No relationship-graph import. No un-merge UI** (pointer-null by hand only). Re-run shows `createdCount: 0`.
+- *Exit:* AC contacts are unified canonical members; re-import is idempotent; the gravity graph has true nodes to grow edges on.
+
+### M — "Three sources + safe, persistent review"
+- **Posh + Luma adapters** — backfill thin historical attendance as NoBC-native, source-tagged rows (nodes + "was here" signal; **no manufactured edges**).
+- `MemberMatchCandidate` persisted queue with **rejection memory** → review is idempotent across re-imports.
+- `MemberMergeEvent` log + a real **`unMerge()`** code path (§5.3) → reversibility is a function, not a claim.
+- Full review-queue UX (§7) with provenance chips, evidence receipts, pre-merge `repointed` preview.
+- Batch observability surface (`ImportBatch` history).
+
+### L — "Scale, incremental sync, survivorship"
+- Cross-source fuzzy matching at scale with confidence scoring + bulk-review ergonomics.
+- Scheduled / API incremental sync (AC API, Luma API) — not just one-shot CSV.
+- **Field-level survivorship** when sources disagree (which source wins per field), feeding `fieldProvenance` `{value, source, confidence, syncedAt}` — the schema already anticipates this.
+- Multi-tenant generalization (Tenant Zero → SaaS): per-tenant source credentials, per-tenant adapter config.
+
+---
+
+## 11. Concrete reuse map (so the build doesn't reinvent)
+
+| Need | Reuse |
+|---|---|
+| Create/resolve a person from a row | `resolveMember()` — never raw `member.create` |
+| Normalize email/phone/IG | `normEmail`/`normPhone`/`normInstagram` in `lib/member-merge.ts` |
+| Auto-merge exact email | `autoMergeExactEmailDuplicates()` |
+| Confirm a phone/IG/name match | `findMergeCandidates()` + `executeMerge()` |
+| AC tags/segments | `Tag` + `TagSource.activecampaign` + `@@unique([workspaceId, externalSource, externalId])` |
+| Per-field provenance/survivorship | `Member.fieldProvenance` (already `{value, source, confidence, syncedAt}`) |
+| Additive migration | `prisma/sql/additive_*.sql` + `prisma db execute --file` |
+| Role gating | `requireRole` / `requireRolePage` |
+
+---
+
+## 12. Open decisions — DO NOT ASSUME
+
+1. **Sample exports first.** Obtain **one real export per source** (Posh, Luma, AC) and lock the §3 capability matrix + each adapter's field map against reality before freezing anything. *Blocks adapter design.*
+2. **Phone/IG auto-merge?** Brief says auto-merge phone/IG-exact; shipped engine deliberately makes them operator-confirm. Recommend: keep silent auto = email only, phone/IG = one-click-confirm in the queue. **Adam decides.**
+3. **Phone normalization scope** — adopt libphonenumber/E.164, or accept the current US-centric `normPhone`? Affects international match accuracy.
+4. **`source` typing** — string vs a new `MemberSource` enum (`posh`/`luma`/`activecampaign`). Enum is safer but is a schema commitment; string is looser. (AC tags already have `TagSource`.)
+5. **Stable per-row key** — which durable ID each source export carries; where absent, the exact hash recipe (`source+email` vs `source+email+eventId`). Per-source, set from §12.1 samples.
+6. **Co-registration / group orders** — do we surface buyer→guest co-registration as a *weak operator-reviewable hint*, or drop it entirely? It is **not** a provable `brought` edge and must never auto-feed gravity (§3, "met" law).
+7. **Un-merge fidelity** — node-level pointer-null vs full history restoration via `MemberMergeEvent` (§5.3). Determines reversal trustworthiness and build weight.
+8. **No-email patrons (ties to stage-16 `OPEN-CAPTURE-1`)** — Instagram-only imports have no email but `Member.email` is required and unique. Mint synthetic emails (then un-dedupable by email, dup risk) or skip no-email rows? Resolve jointly with the CRM capture decision, not separately.
+9. **Email collisions = two real people, one email** (couples sharing an address). `@@unique([workspaceId, email])` makes the second silently resolve into the first — a **silent mis-merge**. Decide a guard (e.g. flag-for-review when an inbound name diverges sharply from the matched row's name).
+10. **Historical attendance scope (M)** — do Posh/Luma backfilled check-ins count toward the Gravity Ledger's "stuck"/lapse thresholds, or are those forward-only? Export fidelity is weak (§3); decide before the engine reads backfilled rows.
+11. **`PROVENANCE_SOURCES` union** — add `posh`/`luma`/`activecampaign` individually (per-platform attribution), or a single `'import'` key (simpler, loses platform detail)? Once DB rows carry a value, renaming it is a migration. (§4.4.)
+
+---
+
+*End of scope. File-only; nothing here has touched the schema, the client, or the database.*
