+# NoBC OS — Positioning Verdict
+> Crest. 2026-06-10. Grounded in PLATFORM-RATING, PRODUCER-OPERATOR-STRATEGY §10, STRATEGY-GTM-CUSTOMER-1, WEDGE-SLICE-PHASE-PLAN, STATE-OF-PLAY.
+
+---
+
+## Diagnosis
+
+The platform is functionally complete on front-of-house but structurally incomplete on the one thing that justifies its existence as a business — money moves through a single Stripe account (zero creators can get paid), "Remember" is an engine with no finished operator surface, and run-of-show is a text field. The product rate-limited itself by over-building consolidation (hardening, DAM, AI breadth) before proving the revenue loop. The thesis is real; the execution sequence is misaligned with the thesis.
+
+---
+
+## Verdict: Onto something — under one specific condition
+
+Not a waste. The bet is structurally sound for one reason hard to copy: the relationship graph cuts across the front/back-of-house line in a way that Lu.ma, Posh, and Partiful are architecturally not positioned to replicate. A sponsor is both a back-of-house contract and a front-of-house logo. A guest is both a ticket buyer and a cross-event revenue signal. Gravity-in-dollars across a unified identity graph cannot be bolted onto a social-graph front-of-house tool without rebuilding from scratch. Lu.ma has no incentive to do that. Posh has no capacity. Partiful just shipped ticketing — they are 18 months behind even front-of-house parity.
+
+**Condition for "onto something":** back-of-house (run-of-show, vendor ops) and revenue rails (Stripe Connect) ship before a second competitor crosses the back-of-house threshold. Partiful's ticketing launch (June 2) starts the clock — roughly 2 quarters before the "they'll never build it" premise is fully dead.
+
+**Condition for "waste":** continued consolidation (hardening, AI breadth, DAM polish) while Stripe Connect stays at zero code. Every month without a creator who can receive money, the platform rates as "a nicer Posh." Nicer loses to free-plus-network.
+
+---
+
+## Positioning Statement
+
+For local recurring event brands that have outgrown Lu.ma's feature ceiling, NoBC is the end-to-end event operating system — front-of-house experience, production back-end, and a cross-event relationship memory — that makes every event build on the last one, unlike Lu.ma and Posh which reset to zero after every ticket sale.
+
+**Not for:** one-off event organizers, venues (Tripleseat owns that), enterprise clubs (Peoplevine/SevenRooms own that), social-first discovery (Partiful owns that).
+
+---
+
+## Steel-man: Keep going vs. sharpen
+
+**"All-in-one is the moat"** — The gravity graph is the real argument, not feature count. Once a creator runs 3+ events on NoBC, the Ledger knows which 12 people drove 60% of captured revenue, which sponsors converted to repeat attendees, which vendors were reliable. That memory cannot be exported. Switching cost is informational, not contractual. The value comes from connections between layers — no point tool can fake that with an integration. The gravity engine exists. That's the strongest signal the thesis is real.
+
+**"Over-scoped, sharpen the wedge"** — The DAM is a 6-PR feature with zero relationship to the gravity moat. AI breadth (archetype scoring unvalidated against spend/attendance, operator chat, AI event builder) is 4 surfaces at 4/10 quality with no proven outcome loop. House Phone is architecturally sound but it's a shared inbox — it doesn't advance the wedge until wired into the relationship graph. Every week on these is a week Stripe Connect sits at zero code.
+
+**Call:** the all-in-one thesis survives — but only if "all-in-one" means "Create → Sell → Run → Remember, connected," not "everything that could live in an operator dashboard." The DAM is not the moat. The gravity graph is. Ship A, C, D in order. The rest is noise until there's a paying creator.
+
+---
+
+## Producer+Operator Convergence: Moat, Distraction, or Later?
+
+**Correct destination. Wrong current priority.**
+
+Strongest internal argument for convergence: the audience-based split (Producer = back-of-house, Operator = consumer-facing) fragments the relationship graph — a sponsor is both, a person can be member and vendor. That fragmentation directly undermines the crown-jewel thesis.
+
+But Producer is a dev-stage Replit app. Separate DB (unconfirmed but likely), separate Clerk app, Express/Drizzle/Gemini stack. Porting it costs 4–8 weeks before a single creator is paying.
+
+**Decision:** build Phase D (minimum run-of-show) hand-coded directly in Operator — NOT a Producer port. `RunOfShowItem` + `VendorContact`, workspace-scoped, ~2 weeks. That gives enough back-of-house to demo indispensability without paying the convergence cost. Full convergence comes after wedge proof — when 3 paying creators exist and the full production spine is needed. Not before.
+
+Convergence is the moat. It is not the wedge. Do not pay for the moat before the wedge closes.
+
+---
+
+## Execution sequence (binding)
+
+| Priority | Phase | What | Condition |
+|---|---|---|---|
+| 1 | A | Stripe Connect — file platform app immediately (external KYC is the critical path) | UNBLOCKED — start today |
+| 2 | C | Finish "Remember" — no-show derivation, spend rollup, smart segments, returning-guest badge | Parallel with A, pure product |
+| 3 | D | Minimum run-of-show — hand-built in Operator, not a Producer port | Unblocked, after C scoped |
+| 4 | B | Creator onboarding + self-serve brand setup | After A+C land |
+| 5 | E | Hardening + customer-1 launch | After B |
+
+**Not now (explicit):** DAM Phase 5–6, additional AI surfaces, archetype scoring backtesting, Producer convergence, additional hardening sprints, MCP Bearer auth design (in-flight — finish it, don't extend it).
+
+---
+
+## Kill condition
+
+If by month 6: (a) no creator outside the founding team has completed a paid event through the Connect path, or (b) no operator has used run-of-show in a live event, or (c) Partiful ships organizer CRM/check-in analytics — reassess the positioning. The back-of-house story needs validation before doubling down on convergence investment.
+
+---
+
+## The one sentence
+
+You're not over-building the vision — you're under-disciplining the sequence; the moat is real, but it only closes if Stripe Connect ships before more consolidation does.
