+# NoBC OS — Product Strategy Decision (Thesis v2)
+
+> **Crest decision memo. 2026-06-09.** Decides against §10 of
+> `PRODUCER-OPERATOR-STRATEGY.md` (Thesis v2), which supersedes §9. Strategy
+> owner: Adam. This memo is a recommendation to ratify, not a unilateral lock —
+> the five decisions below are the ones §10.6 asked for, made.
+
+---
+
+## Verdict in one line
+
+**Ratify Thesis v2 with one correction: position against the disjointed stack, not
+against Lu.ma — and build the convergence the wedge needs, not the spine for its own
+sake.** The wedge is real and defensible; the risk is sequencing infrastructure ahead
+of proof.
+
+---
+
+## Situation
+
+Operator (`nobc-os`) is mature and in production — a strong front-of-house +
+operator dashboard. Producer is dev-stage, disconnected, and — per the 2026-06-09
+config verification — **genuinely separate** (its own Clerk with no prod instance,
+its own Neon). So "Producer + Operator as one tool," which the entire thesis rests
+on, is not an untangle of a shared system; it is a **greenfield merge of two
+separate systems**, paid by a small team, before a single paying customer has
+validated that the merged product is indispensable. The honest tension: the thesis's
+crown jewel (front + back in one connected graph) is the part least built, and
+building it is heavier than the old roadmap assumed. There is no fire (separate DBs
+can't drop each other's tables), so this can be designed deliberately — the danger
+is not urgency, it's spending the team's runway on spine infrastructure before
+proving the wedge.
+
+## Insight
+
+There is a real, specific gap in the market, and it is not "Lu.ma but nicer." The
+front-of-house is owned by excellent, free, network-effected tools (Lu.ma, Posh,
+Partiful) that treat **every event as a blank slate** and have **no reason to build
+production back-of-house** — it's a low-volume, high-touch, vertical surface that is
+off-strategy for a horizontal PLG consumer player. The back-of-house is owned by
+Tripleseat-class tools that are venue-shaped, enterprise-sales, dated, and useless to
+an independent creator. **Nobody serves the local, fast-paced, growing creator who is
+currently duct-taping Lu.ma + a spreadsheet + email + Stripe + a notes-app CRM.** The
+founder pain — "sick of the disjointed systems that each do 1/10 of what I need" — *is*
+the market gap. That is the enemy to position against: the disjointed stack, not Lu.ma.
+And the lock-in is **compounding**: on Lu.ma, event #2 starts from zero; on NoBC, event
+#2 already knows your regulars, your vendors, your money, your sponsors. The relationship
+graph that compounds across events is the thing a front-of-house tool structurally cannot
+give you.
+
+## The decisions (answering §10.6 a–e)
+
+### (a) Validate the wedge — DEFENSIBLE, with one reframe
+
+"Indispensable end-to-end tool for local growing event brands" is defensible against
+Lu.ma, Posh, Partiful, and Tripleseat — **but the moat is the back-of-house + the
+compounding graph, never the front.** Front-of-house parity is table stakes and the
+credibility cost of entry, not the differentiator. Reframe the wedge: **we don't beat
+Lu.ma, we replace the stack.** Lu.ma "will never build" the production/sponsor back-end
+not because they can't but because it's off-strategy for a horizontal free consumer
+product — that's a credible, durable "they won't," which is what makes it defensible.
+
+### (b) The narrowest end-to-end slice — "Create → Sell → Run → Remember a recurring event"
+
+The slice that makes a creator never go back is the **recurring-event creator** (supper-
+club series, party series, pop-ups, experiential brands) running **one series end-to-end**:
+
+1. **Create + Sell** — beautiful event page, registration, ticketing (front-of-house parity).
+2. **Run** — day-of execution: check-in (built) + the minimum production back-of-house
+   (run-of-show + vendor coordination for that event).
+3. **Remember** — the persistent guest/vendor/sponsor CRM that **compounds across events.**
+
+The "never go back" moment is **event #2**: on Lu.ma it's a blank slate; on NoBC it
+inherits the relationship graph. "Remember" is the verb no front-of-house tool owns, and
+it is the relationship spine in its minimal, wedge-justifying form. **Resolve the
+"indispensable = broad" tension by holding this slice narrow:** breadth is the eventual
+moat, but the wedge is these four verbs for one recurring creator — nothing more until
+one creator won't go back.
+
+### (c) Sequence the three constituencies — creators → members (PLG) → sponsors (fast-follow)
+
+- **Creators (now–6mo, founder-led):** NoBC + Chloe + 3–5 design-partner local creators.
+  This is the wedge.
+- **Members/guests (overlapping, the growth engine):** not a later phase — a **quality bar
+  on the front-of-house from day one.** The attendee experience must visibly beat Lu.ma so
+  guests ask "what is this?" → the attendee-to-creator viral loop (Lu.ma's own proven
+  motion). Growth is bottom-up and earned at the door, every event.
+- **Sponsors (9–18mo, fast-follow):** monetization, served as a **back-office capability for
+  creators who already sell sponsorships** (NoBC, design partners) — NOT a SaaS promise that
+  "we'll get you sponsors." This de-risks the weakest SaaS link (§9.3 hole #3): sponsor
+  tooling is gold for those who have sponsor relationships and must never be sold as a
+  marketplace guarantee to those who don't.
+
+### (d) Revenue model — land on transaction fees, expand to subscription
+
+Named explicitly (this was the unfilled hole, §10.5 #3): **two streams, PLG-aligned.**
+
+1. **Transaction fees (primary, land):** free to create; take a competitive % of paid
+   tickets. Removes adoption friction, scales with creator GMV, funds the bottom-up motion.
+   This is the Lu.ma/Posh-compatible front-door.
+2. **Creator subscription (expand, the indispensability capture):** the back-of-house —
+   production ops, persistent CRM, vendor coordination, sponsor tooling — is the **paid
+   monthly tier.** The free front-of-house is the wedge; the back-of-house is what you pay to
+   keep because your whole operation runs on it.
+
+One sentence: **"Free to run your events (we take a ticket cut); pay monthly once you run
+your operation on us."** Land-free, expand-to-paid — proven PLG SaaS, and perfectly aligned
+with the wedge (the thing that makes you never go back is the thing you pay for). Sponsor
+revenue-share is a deferred third stream, not part of the early model.
+
+### (e) Convergence + intelligence — convergence is the MEANS (confirmed, re-sequenced); intelligence/comms DEFERRED
+
+- **Convergence: CONFIRMED as mandatory but RE-SEQUENCED.** "Front + back in one connected
+  graph" is structurally impossible without merging Operator + Producer — the audience-based
+  split (§9.2) fragments the exact graph that is the whole point. **But do not front-load the
+  full Identity→CRM→Event spine before the wedge is proven** (that's the §6 roadmap's order,
+  and it's backwards for v2). Build the *minimum* convergence the slice in (b) needs — a
+  persistent guest/vendor CRM + day-of run-of-show — validate "won't go back," then deepen the
+  spine. Given Producer is dev-stage and separate, **port only the 1–2 back-of-house
+  capabilities the wedge needs; defer the full Producer migration.** This directly de-risks
+  holes #2 (scope) and #4 (execution load).
+- **Intelligence + §9.5 comms-ingestion layer: DEFERRED moat-deepeners, demotion CONFIRMED.**
+  "Analytics without insight is a trap" (§10.1) is correct. The comms layer is deep, privacy-
+  heavy, and volume-dependent — it sharpens the execution-risk holes and earns its place only
+  after the wedge is proven and there's comms volume to mine. The ONLY intelligence that earns
+  early inclusion is the actionable kind welded to the wedge: *"12 regulars haven't come in 60
+  days," "this vendor is slow to respond"* — insight that triggers an action, not a dashboard.
+
+## What we're explicitly NOT doing
+
+- **Not leading with "Soho-House-tier member clubs"** (supersedes §3's target). Membership is a
+  **mode you switch on**, not the lead segment. Lead with the local growing *creator* where
+  Lu.ma is the incumbent and the wedge is sharpest; NoBC is tenant-zero proof of membership-mode.
+- **Not building the full Identity→CRM→Event spine before a creator hits "won't go back."**
+  Convergence is wedge-driven, not infrastructure-first.
+- **Not migrating Producer off Replit/Express/Drizzle as an early step.** Port the minimum
+  back-of-house surface the wedge needs; defer the rest.
+- **Not building the comms-ingestion / intelligence layer now.** Deferred moat-deepener.
+- **Not selling sponsors as a SaaS promise.** Back-office capability for those who already have
+  sponsor relationships; never a "we'll get you sponsors" guarantee.
+- **Not the broad "OS for people who gather people."** That's the expansion narrative, not the
+  wedge — it stays out of the GTM story until the narrow slice is won.
+
+## Success criteria (~2 quarters / 6 months)
+
+- **North Star: active recurring creators** — creators who ran **≥2 real events in 90 days**
+  end-to-end on NoBC. This is the indispensability proxy: they came back.
+- **Milestones:** (1) 3–5 design-partner creators running real series end-to-end; (2) front-
+  of-house at demonstrable parity — a creator chooses NoBC over Lu.ma for a real public event;
+  (3) ≥1 creator who explicitly says they won't go back **and** uses the back-of-house weekly;
+  (4) revenue live — ticket fees flowing + ≥1 paid creator subscription.
+- **Learning goals:** Does compounding/"Remember" actually retain? Will a non-NoBC creator pay
+  for the back-of-house? Does the attendee→creator referral loop fire?
+
+## Review conditions (what changes the bet)
+
+- **If, by ~6mo, no creator hits the "won't go back" bar with the back-of-house** → the wedge is
+  "just another Lu.ma." Revisit whether the back-of-house we built is the right one.
+- **If front-of-house can't reach parity** (creators keep choosing Lu.ma for the page) → the
+  wedge's credibility fails; reconsider competing on front at all vs. integrating with Lu.ma.
+- **If design partners won't pay the subscription** → revenue model is wrong; lean on transaction
+  fees and rethink what sits behind the paywall.
+- **If convergence cost balloons** (the Producer merge consumes the team before the wedge is
+  proven) → stop the spine build, hand-build the minimum back-of-house inside Operator, shelve
+  Producer.
+- **If Lu.ma/Posh ship a credible production/sponsor back-end** → the "they'll never build it"
+  premise is dead; re-evaluate the moat immediately.
+```
+
+---
+
+## Immediate next action
+
+Hand the **narrowest-slice scope** (the "Create → Sell → Run → Remember" recurring-event
+flow, and the minimum Producer back-of-house it pulls in) to a planner/architect as a
+phase definition — **before** any CRM-spine ADR or Producer migration. Validate the wedge
+with one design-partner creator first. Spine deepening follows proof, not precedes it.
