+# NoBC OS — GTM, Pricing & Customer 1 (Thesis v2 companion)
+
+> **Crest memo #2. 2026-06-09.** Companion to `STRATEGY-DECISION-THESIS-V2.md`.
+> That memo made the strategy decision; this one operationalizes it — ICP,
+> pricing, GTM, expected cost, and the plan to land customer 1.
+> Competitive pricing verified against live sources 2026-06-09.
+
+---
+
+## 1. The competitive pricing map (verified 2026-06-09)
+
+| Tool | Model | What the creator pays |
+|---|---|---|
+| **Lu.ma** | Free + 5% platform fee on paid tickets; Plus = $59/mo → 0% fee | 5% or $59/mo |
+| **Posh** | 10% + $0.99/ticket, passed to attendees | Attendees eat ~12–14% effective |
+| **Eventbrite** | 3.7% + $1.79/ticket + 2.9% processing; fee caps removed 2026 | ~10% effective on a $50 ticket |
+| **Partiful** | Free; **ticketing launched 2026-06-02** | TBD — watch closely |
+| **Tripleseat** | Custom enterprise quote (venue-shaped) | est. $300–500+/mo, sales-led |
+| **HoneyBook** | $36–129/mo back-office SaaS (closest subscription anchor) | $36–129/mo |
+
+Two strategic reads:
+1. **The front-of-house fee corridor is 5–10%.** Lu.ma set the floor; Posh proves
+   nightlife creators tolerate 10%+ passed to attendees. NoBC can price inside the
+   corridor and never lose on price.
+2. **⚠️ Partiful shipping ticketing (June 2) is the first move by a free social
+   player toward monetized events.** It validates the space and starts the clock on
+   the "they'll never build the back-end" premise. Tripwire added to §8.
+
+---
+
+## 2. The ICP — sharpened to a person
+
+**The recurring local event brand operator.** Not a venue, not a corporate planner,
+not enterprise luxury.
+
+**Firmographics:**
+- 1–3 person team (founder + a partner/contractor), often founder = creative director
+  = door person = bookkeeper
+- Runs a **named series** — supper club, party/music series, wellness pop-up, culture
+  brand — 2–4 events/month, 75–500 attendees, $20–100 tickets
+- $5k–50k/month ticket GMV; growing; has or wants **sponsor relationships**
+- Tools today: Posh or Eventbrite or Lu.ma (front) + Google Sheets + IG DMs + group
+  chats + Stripe/Venmo + a notes app (back). Pays for 3–6 tools that each do 1/10.
+
+**Psychographics:** brand-proud (their event page IS their brand), time-starved,
+revenue-sensitive (a 10% Posh fee on $20k/mo is $2k/mo — they feel it), and ambitious
+— they want to look bigger than they are to sponsors and venues.
+
+**Who it is NOT (hold the line):** one-off party hosts (Partiful's turf), big venues
+(Tripleseat's), conference organizers, enterprise luxury brands (§10.2 explicitly
+rejected), free-community organizers with no ticket revenue (no GMV to monetize).
+
+**It is literally Adam and Chloe twelve months ago.** Founder-market fit is the
+targeting algorithm: customer 1 looks like the founder.
+
+---
+
+## 3. Why they buy (the pitch, in their words)
+
+Ranked by what closes:
+
+1. **"Stop paying Posh 10% — keep the difference."** Switching $20k/mo GMV from
+   Posh (10% + $0.99) to NoBC at 5% all-in saves ~$1,200+/mo. **The fee delta alone
+   pays for the subscription several times over.** This is the spreadsheet-proof,
+   CFO-grade reason to switch — lead with it.
+2. **"Your event #2 isn't a blank slate."** Regulars, no-shows, comp lists, big
+   spenders, the vendor who was late — carried forward automatically. Lu.ma/Posh
+   structurally can't do this; it's the compounding "Remember" wedge.
+3. **"Look like a real brand, not a listing."** White-label, premium, editorial
+   event pages (already built — the 7-theme system + editorial redesign). Posh pages
+   look like Posh; NoBC pages look like *the creator's brand*.
+4. **"One tool instead of six."** Registration + tickets + check-in + guest CRM +
+   run-of-show + sponsor one-pager. The disjointed stack is the enemy (per the
+   decision memo) — this is the indispensability story.
+5. **"Walk into your sponsor meeting with real numbers."** Attendance, repeat rate,
+   demographics from actual data. Fast-follow, but it's the *aspiration* that makes
+   them lean in during the pitch.
+
+**The buying trigger** to watch for: a creator who just had a fee shock (Posh/EB
+payout statement), a door disaster (no check-in system), or a sponsor ask they
+couldn't answer with data.
+
+---
+
+## 4. Pricing — what we ask for
+
+**Two streams, exactly per the decision memo (land = fees, expand = subscription):**
+
+### Front-of-house (land — free to start)
+- **Free plan: 5% platform fee on paid tickets** (+ Stripe passthrough). Matches
+  Lu.ma's free plan, dramatically undercuts Posh/Eventbrite. Free events: $0 forever.
+- Never compete above Lu.ma's 5%; never give it away below (we don't have their
+  network effects to subsidize 0%).
+
+### Back-of-house (expand — the subscription)
+- **List price: $199/mo** ("Operator" tier): persistent guest/vendor/sponsor CRM,
+  run-of-show, check-in PWA, comp/red-list, sponsor reporting, white-label themes,
+  **0% platform fee on tickets** (the Lu.ma Plus move — the subscription eats the fee).
+- **Founding-partner price: $99/mo, locked for life**, for the first 5–10 design
+  partners. Charge from month one — a paid pilot is the validation; free pilots
+  validate nothing.
+- Anchors: above HoneyBook's $36–129 generalist range (we're vertical and replace
+  more), far below Tripleseat's enterprise quote. $199 is a defensible vertical-SaaS
+  price for a business doing $10k+/mo GMV.
+
+### The self-financing switch (why $199 is easy)
+At $20k/mo GMV on Posh, the creator's audience pays ~$2,400/mo in fees. On NoBC
+Operator at $199/mo + 0% platform fee, the all-in cost drops by ~$2,200/mo (Stripe
+aside). **The subscription is cheaper than their current fees.** That's the whole
+close.
+
+### Unit economics per ICP customer
+- Free-tier creator at $15k/mo GMV → ~$750/mo in platform fees ≈ **$9k ARR equivalent**
+- Operator-tier creator → $199/mo ≈ **$2.4k ARR** + retention/expansion
+- Blended target ACV: **$2.5–9k.** Ten ICP customers ≈ $25–90k ARR — a real seed-stage
+  proof line from a tiny base.
+
+---
+
+## 5. GTM strategy — founder-led, one-city density, events as the funnel
+
+**Phase 0 — Tenant zero as the demo (now → 2 months).**
+NoBC runs 100% of its own events on the platform. Every NoBC event is a live product
+demo: the page, the door scan, the wallet pass, the vibe. Instrument everything —
+"we grew repeat attendance X% using our own tool" becomes the case study. Capture
+attendee→creator interest at the door ("powered by" footer + a creator waitlist link).
+
+**Phase 1 — 5 design partners (months 1–4).**
+Hand-picked from Adam + Chloe's first-degree network in ONE city. Criteria: recurring
+series, 2+ events/month, paid tickets, currently on Posh/EB/Lu.ma, founder reachable
+by text. Offer: $99/mo founding rate locked for life + **concierge migration** (we
+move their guest list, build their first event page with them, work their door at
+event #1). Ask in return: weekly feedback, a testimonial, and logo rights.
+**Customer 1 closes here — see §6.**
+
+**Phase 2 — city density (months 4–9).**
+10–20 creators in the same metro. Density makes the attendee→creator loop fire:
+the same attendees go to multiple NoBC-powered events, recognize the experience,
+and the creators all know each other (local event scenes are villages — word of
+mouth is the channel). Add a public "powered by NoBC" creator directory for the city.
+
+**Channels, ranked:** (1) founder network + NoBC's own events; (2) creator-to-creator
+referral inside the city scene; (3) the attendee loop ("powered by" → waitlist);
+(4) content — Adam's newsletter + IG documenting the build and the events. **No paid
+acquisition, no outbound SDR, no second city until density works in city one.**
+
+**Positioning one-liner (per the decision memo — enemy is the stack, not Lu.ma):**
+> "Run your whole event brand in one place. Lu.ma-grade pages and ticketing in front;
+> the guest memory, production ops, and sponsor engine they'll never build in back —
+> and your audience stops paying 10% fees."
+
+**Sales motion:** founder-led, in-person/DM, demo = an actual NoBC event. Close on
+the fee-savings spreadsheet (§3.1). Time-to-value bar: **first event live in under
+1 hour, guest list migrated in under a day** (concierge does it for them).
+
+---
+
+## 6. Customer 1 — the spec
+
+**Profile:** a local recurring series operator in Adam's own scene — supper club,
+party series, or culture brand. 2–4 paid events/month, 100–300 attendees, $25–75
+tickets, $8–25k/mo GMV, currently on **Posh** (the fee pain is sharpest there) or
+Eventbrite + spreadsheets. Knows Adam or is one intro away. Brand-proud — embarrassed
+that their page looks like everyone else's Posh page.
+
+**Why Posh-first as the poach target:** their audience pays ~12–14% effective fees,
+the all-in-pricing rules make those fees visible, and the organizer can't white-label.
+Highest pain + cleanest savings math + brand vanity = fastest switch.
+
+**The offer:** $99/mo for life + 5%→0% platform fee + we migrate everything + Adam
+personally works the door at their first NoBC event. They cannot get this deal later.
+
+**Definition of won (matches the North Star):** ran **2+ consecutive real events**
+end-to-end on NoBC, used the back-of-house (CRM/run-of-show) between events without
+prompting, paying the $99, and said some version of "I'm not going back."
+
+**Realistic timeline:** signed inside 30 days of the wedge slice being demo-able;
+"won" by event #2 (~30–60 days after signing).
+
+---
+
+## 7. Expected cost (6-month horizon)
+
+**Cash costs — lean, because the build is founder + AI:**
+
+| Bucket | Monthly | 6-mo total |
+|---|---|---|
+| Infra (Vercel, Neon, Clerk, Resend, R2, Railway, Twilio) | $150–400 | $1–2.5k |
+| Anthropic API (scoring, intelligence, House Phone) | $100–400 | $0.6–2.5k |
+| Tooling (Claude Code, Doppler, misc SaaS) | $150–250 | $1–1.5k |
+| Stripe (passthrough, netted from fees) | — | — |
+| Design partner concierge (door hardware, comps, misc) | ~$150 | ~$1k |
+| Legal (ToS/fee terms review — fee handling is new surface) | one-time | $2–4k |
+| **Total cash** | | **≈ $6–11k** |
+
+**The real cost is build time (opportunity cost, not cash):**
+- Wedge slice remaining ≈ **2.5–4 founder-months**: minimum Producer back-of-house
+  port (run-of-show + vendor coordination inside Operator), the "Remember" CRM
+  surface (guest history across events), platform-fee billing on Stripe, creator
+  onboarding/migration flow. At contractor-equivalent rates that's $40–70k of
+  engineering; actual cash ≈ $0 beyond the table above.
+- Operator is already mature (V1 functionally complete) — most of the front-of-house
+  parity is **already paid for.** The spend is back-of-house + billing + onboarding.
+
+**6-month all-in: ~$10–15k cash + ~3 founder-months.** Break-even on cash at roughly
+**5–6 founding-tier customers or ~$200k/mo of free-tier GMV** — both inside the
+Phase 1 plan.
+
+---
+
+## 8. Tripwires (additions to the decision memo's review conditions)
+
+- **Partiful ticketing (launched 2026-06-02):** if Partiful ships organizer tools
+  (CRM, check-in analytics, payouts maturity) within 2 quarters, the front-of-house
+  free corridor gets more crowded — accelerate back-of-house differentiation, do not
+  fight them on social features.
+- **Lu.ma moves down-market on ops** (vendor/run-of-show features): the "never build
+  it" premise weakens — re-evaluate within 30 days of any such launch.
+- **Fee revenue concentration:** if >80% of revenue is platform fees and no one
+  upgrades to Operator tier by month 6, the indispensability thesis is failing —
+  the back-of-house isn't valuable enough yet. That's a product alarm, not a
+  pricing alarm.
+
+---
+
+## Sources
+
+- [Luma Pricing](https://luma.com/pricing) · [Luma Plus Overview](https://help.luma.com/p/luma-plus-overview) · [Creating a Paid Event — Luma](https://help.luma.com/p/creating-a-paid-event)
