+# Data Audit — 2026-06-09
+
+**Verdict:** Schema design and workspace-scoping discipline are strong, but there is large, real migration-history drift — a whole slice of the live schema (`MemberPsychographics`, `FieldDefinition`, `Member` dimension columns, `RecapSnapshot`, `SurveyResponse`, the sponsor firewall view, and several indexes) was applied via hand-run out-of-band SQL and has NO entry in `prisma/migrations/`, so the next `prisma migrate` run will see it as drift. This is the dominant risk and must be reconciled before any tracked migration is created.
+
+---
+
+### [CRITICAL] Tracked migrations diverge from the live schema — out-of-band SQL was never recorded as migrations
+
+A large portion of `schema.prisma` exists in the production DB only because someone ran the files in `prisma/sql/` by hand. None of it is in `prisma/migrations/`. Cross-referenced objects with **0 tracked migrations**:
+
+- `MemberPsychographics` table (schema.prisma:249) — only in `prisma/sql/additive_pr2_dimensions.sql`
+- `FieldDefinition` table (schema.prisma:267) — only in `additive_pr2_dimensions.sql`
+- `Member.customFields`, `fieldProvenance`, `city`, `country`, `companyName`, `companyDomain`, `linkedinUrl`, `instagram`, `enrichmentStatus`, `enrichmentLastSynced` (schema.prisma:198-207) — only in `additive_pr2_dimensions.sql`
+- `MemberEnrichmentStatus` enum (schema.prisma:237) — only in `additive_pr2_dimensions.sql`
+- `Member.mergedIntoId` / `mergedAt` + `Member_mergedIntoId_idx` + `RSVP_memberId_idx` + `Member_workspaceId_phone_idx` (schema.prisma:182-183, 233-234) — only in `additive_member_merge.sql`
+- `RecapSnapshot` table (schema.prisma:1255) + `SponsorBrandProfile.declaredObjectives/targetPersonaCriteria/rightsFeeCents` (schema.prisma:1235-1237) — only in `sponsor-intel-p0.sql`
+- `SurveyResponse` table + `SurveyPhase` enum (schema.prisma:1294, 1300) — only in `sponsor-intel-p1.sql`
+- `EventCustomQuestion.sponsorBrandId` + index/FK (schema.prisma:514) — only in `sponsor-intel-p2.sql`
+- `EventSeries.defaultCapacity` / `defaultEventAccess` (schema.prisma:944-947) — only in `series-defaults.sql`
+- `sponsor_audience_member` view — only in `sponsor-audience-view.sql`
+
+The `_prisma_migrations` table therefore does not record these as applied. Anyone who runs `prisma migrate dev`/`prisma migrate diff --from-migrations` will get a non-empty diff that tries to **re-create** these objects (CREATE TABLE will fail) or, worse, prompts a baseline reset. Combined with the CLAUDE.md ban on `db push`, the project has effectively no working forward-migration path right now — every change is a hand-curated SQL file, which is how the next item happened.
+
+**Fix:** Reconcile history without touching data. For each out-of-band SQL file, create a matching `prisma/migrations/<timestamp>_<name>/migration.sql` whose body is the (idempotent) SQL already applied, then mark it applied in prod with `prisma migrate resolve --applied <migration_name>` (which only writes a `_prisma_migrations` row — no DDL). Do this on the Neon instance in coordination with Producer. After reconciliation, `prisma migrate diff --from-migrations prisma/migrations --to-schema-datamodel prisma/schema.prisma --script` should be empty except for the known `Asset_searchVector_idx` GIN line. Keep the "review the diff, refuse DROP/ALTER TYPE/RENAME, apply with `db execute`" workflow for future changes — but record each as a resolved migration so history stops drifting.
+
+---
+
+### [CRITICAL] `MemberEngagementEventType` enum: tracked migration defines 8 values, schema + code use 18
+
+`prisma/migrations/20260525000000_add_referral_linkage_engagement_events/migration.sql` creates the enum with exactly 8 values (`rsvp_confirmed` … `sponsor_perk_clicked`). `schema.prisma:1470-1491` lists 18 — the extra 10 (`guest_created`, `application_approved`, `application_rejected`, `comp_issued`, `access_requested`, `ticket_purchased`, `plus_one_added`, `referral_made`, `enrichment_synced`, `merged`) exist in prod only via `prisma/sql/additive_engagement_enum.sql`, which is not a tracked migration.
+
+Consequences: (1) a fresh DB built from `prisma/migrations/` alone (CI shadow DB, a new tenant bootstrap, Producer's own migrate run) gets an 8-value enum, and any `emitEvent` write of one of the 10 new values throws `invalid input value for enum`. (2) `prisma migrate diff` reports the 10 values as drift. Because Producer shares this instance, a Producer-side `migrate` that rebuilds from tracked history would not know the values were added.
+
+**Fix:** Add a tracked migration containing the `ALTER TYPE "MemberEngagementEventType" ADD VALUE IF NOT EXISTS ...` statements from `additive_engagement_enum.sql` (note the Postgres caveat already documented there: `ADD VALUE` cannot run in the same transaction that uses the value, so keep these as standalone statements / their own migration), then `prisma migrate resolve --applied` it against prod. Verify with a count of `pg_enum` rows for the type = 18.
+
+---
+
+### [WARNING] The sponsor firewall VIEW is defined but never queried — the real firewall is per-call `select` discipline
+
+`prisma/sql/sponsor-audience-view.sql` builds `sponsor_audience_member` as "the ONLY member shape sponsor-facing aggregation may read," and `tests/unit/sponsor-firewall.test.ts` asserts on the view's text (no JOIN, no `SELECT *`, both WHERE invariants). But `grep` for `sponsor_audience_member` across `lib/` and `app/` returns **zero runtime readers**. The actual sponsor aggregation reads the base table directly: `lib/intelligence/metrics.ts:254` does `db.member.findMany({ where: { workspaceId, status: 'APPROVED' }, select: { email, industry, seniority, companySize } })` and pulls `archetype` from `Application`, not `MemberPsychographics`.
+
+This is currently safe — the hand-written `select` is firmographic-only and the firewall test scans the named sponsor-facing files for psychographic tokens — but the defense-in-depth the view was meant to provide is not wired in. The view's `status='APPROVED' AND mergedIntoId IS NULL` invariants are not automatically applied to ad-hoc `db.member` reads; `metrics.ts:254` happens to filter `status:'APPROVED'` but does NOT filter `mergedIntoId IS NULL`, so soft-merged duplicates can be double-counted in sponsor audience size (the exact case the view's WHERE was written to prevent — see `additive_member_merge.sql` and the view comment).
+
+**Fix:** Either (a) route sponsor-facing member reads through the `sponsor_audience_member` view (e.g. a `db.$queryRaw` against the view, or a Prisma view model) so the two invariants can't be forgotten, or (b) at minimum add `mergedIntoId: null` to the `where` in `lib/intelligence/metrics.ts:254` (and any sibling sponsor aggregate) and extend `sponsor-firewall.test.ts` to assert the dedup filter is present on those queries. Option (a) is the design the SQL/comments already promise.
+
+---
+
+### [WARNING] Out-of-band SQL targets `$DIRECT_URL` / an unpooled endpoint that is not configured anywhere
+
+Multiple `prisma/sql/*.sql` headers instruct operators to run `DATABASE_URL="$DIRECT_URL" ... db execute` "on the UNPOOLED endpoint" (`additive_pr2_dimensions.sql`, `sponsor-audience-view.sql`). But there is no `DIRECT_URL` in `.env.local.example`, no `directUrl` in the `datasource` block (schema.prisma:5-7), and `prisma.config.ts` wires only `process.env.DATABASE_URL`. `lib/db.ts` uses `PrismaNeon({ connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL })` — the pooled string.
+
+Running DDL (especially `CREATE TYPE` / `ALTER TYPE ... ADD VALUE` and trigger/function creation) through PgBouncer transaction-pooling can fail or behave inconsistently. The instructions assume a variable the repo never defines, so whoever runs these will silently fall back to the pooled `DATABASE_URL`.
+
+**Fix:** Add `DIRECT_URL` (Neon unpooled `-pooler`-less host) to `.env.local.example` and reference it via `directUrl` in the `datasource` block so `prisma migrate`/`db execute` use it. Update the SQL headers to name the actual env var the repo provides. This also future-proofs the migration-reconciliation work in the CRITICAL items above.
+
+---
+
+### [INFO] `Order` / `TicketTier` / `AccessToken` / `PromoCode` "XOR eventId/seriesId" is comment-only, not DB-enforced
+
+`schema.prisma:990, 1069, 1137` document "exactly one of eventId or seriesId must be set," but both columns are plain nullable with no `CHECK` constraint or partial unique index. A bug or a Producer-side write could set both or neither, and pricing/inventory logic that assumes the XOR would misbehave. Low likelihood given app-level discipline, hence INFO.
+
+**Fix (optional, additive):** Add a `CHECK ((("eventId" IS NOT NULL)::int + ("seriesId" IS NOT NULL)::int) = 1)` constraint per table via a hand-reviewed additive migration (a CHECK is additive and Producer-safe). Validate existing rows satisfy it first.
+
+---
+
+### [INFO] DAM full-text path is correct and injection-safe — documenting for completeness
+
+The `Asset` GIN index (`Asset_searchVector_idx`) and `searchVector` `Unsupported("tsvector")` are correctly handled: the index lives only in `prisma/sql/dam-search-vector.sql`, schema.prisma:1538 marks the column `Unsupported`, and the CLAUDE.md `db push` ban is the right guard. The raw search query in `app/api/media/dam/assets/route.ts:38` and `lib/dam/search.ts` is parameterized via `Prisma.sql`, always prefixes `workspaceId = ${workspaceId}` (search.ts:76), and `ORDER BY ${order}` interpolates only from the fixed `SORTS` map (search.ts:29-37) with the sort key validated against `Object.keys(SORTS)` (search.ts:42) — no SQL-injection surface. No action needed; flagged so the next auditor doesn't re-investigate.
+
+---
+
+## What's healthy
+
+- **Workspace scoping is consistent.** `workspaceId` is present and `@@index`ed on every user-data model; the one raw-SQL read path (DAM assets) enforces it in the WHERE builder. Identity uniqueness is well-modeled: `Member @@unique([workspaceId, clerkUserId])` + `@@unique([workspaceId, email])`, `WorkspaceMember @@unique([workspaceId, email])`, `Workspace.clerkOrgId @unique`/`slug @unique`, `Event @@unique([workspaceId, slug])`, and token/hash uniqueness on `AccessToken.tokenHash`, `Order.stripePaymentIntentId`, `ShareLink.token`, `Event.producerEventId`, `SurveyResponse.token`.
+- **The additive-migration discipline in `prisma/sql/` is genuinely careful** — every file documents the `Asset_searchVector_idx` false-drift, refuses DROP/ALTER TYPE/RENAME, uses `IF NOT EXISTS` idempotency, and notes Producer-shared-instance safety. The discipline is sound; it just stops short of recording the result as tracked migrations (the CRITICAL findings).
+- **Sponsor firewall as a type + table boundary is well-built.** `MemberPsychographics` is physically separate, `lib/intelligence/sponsor-safe.ts` enforces a compile-time `_SponsorSafe` assertion, and `tests/unit/sponsor-firewall.test.ts` scans sponsor-facing files for psychographic reads. The gap is only that the runtime SQL view isn't wired in (WARNING above).
+- **JSON columns are typed at the edges.** `customFields`/`fieldProvenance` reads/writes go through `lib/member-provenance.ts` and `lib/member-record.ts` with explicit `Record<string, unknown>` casts and a `ProvenanceSource` union shared by the PATCH validator — JSON usage is not free-for-all.
