@@ -0,0 +1,101 @@
+# Frontend Audit — NoBC OS (Accessibility + Performance)
+
+**Date:** 2026-06-09
+**Scope:** READ-ONLY. Accessibility (focus indicators, semantic HTML, Radix adoption) and performance (next/image, code-splitting, monolith components, list virtualization).
+
+---
+
+## Verdict
+
+Solid a11y foundations (global focus-visible ring, skip link, real `<table>`/`<label>` semantics, accessible custom modals) are being quietly defeated by ~93 element-level `focus:outline-none` utilities and undermined by near-zero performance hygiene — a dev/QA client bundle (~3,200 LOC) ships in every operator page, zero `next/image`, and the DAM grid + operator queues render unbounded lists without virtualization.
+
+---
+
+### [WARNING] ~93 `focus:outline-none` utilities can defeat the global keyboard focus ring (specificity, not coverage)
+
+There IS a correct global baseline — `app/globals.css:958` defines `:focus-visible { outline: 2px solid var(--primary); outline-offset: 2px }` plus `:focus:not(:focus-visible) { outline: none }` (lines 965-967), and per-theme `:focus-visible` overrides exist (obsidian/parchment/void/ember). That is the WCAG 2.2 AA intent and it is good.
+
+The problem is element-level overrides. A grep finds **93** `focus:outline-none` / `outline-none` occurrences across `components/` + `app/` vs only **10** `focus-visible` usages, and **zero files combine `outline-none` with a `focus-visible` replacement** (verified: no file containing `outline-none` also contains `focus-visible`). Tailwind's `focus:outline-none` emits `:focus { outline: none }`. Because keyboard focus matches BOTH `:focus` and `:focus-visible`, the winner is decided by source order / specificity — and many of these inputs rely on a `focus:border-…` color change as their only remaining affordance, which is a ~1px color shift that fails the WCAG 2.4.7 (visible focus) + 1.4.11 (non-text contrast) bar on its own.
+
+Representative offenders (color-border-only focus, outline killed):
+- `app/m/events/[slug]/_components/CustomQuestionsForm.tsx:57,65,95` — member registration-field inputs
+- `app/m/events/[slug]/_components/RsvpCard.tsx:171,187` — member access flow inputs
+- `app/m/(portal)/profile/_components/ProfileForm.tsx:66` — shared input class
+- `app/operator/applications/_components/ApplicationsQueue.tsx:548,555,1208` — search/filter/note inputs
+- `app/operator/settings/communications/_components/CommunicationsEditor.tsx:197,206,215,354,362`
+- `app/operator/house-phone/HousePhoneClient.tsx:302,438` — `outline-none` with no `focus:` replacement at all
+- `app/operator/intelligence/recap/_components/RecapStudio.tsx:23` — `fieldClass` with bare `outline-none`
+- `components/intelligence/InsightComposer.tsx:93` — bare `outline-none`
+
+**Fix:** Stop killing the outline on focusable controls. For each `focus:outline-none`, either (a) delete it and let the global `:focus-visible` ring apply, or (b) if a custom ring is wanted, replace with `focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-primary focus-visible:ring-offset-2` so the override only fires for the visible-focus state and still paints a ≥2px high-contrast indicator. Codify it: add an ESLint guard (or a shared input class in one place) that bans bare `focus:outline-none` without a paired `focus-visible:ring-*`. The member-facing `/apply` and event-access inputs are the priority since those are the public surfaces.
+
+### [WARNING] Custom modals are accessible-ish but lack focus trapping and initial focus management
+
+The hand-rolled dialogs are better than typical — `components/ui/ConfirmModal.tsx` has `role="dialog"`, `aria-modal="true"`, Escape-to-close (lines ~22-29), and backdrop click — and 16 `fixed inset-0` modal surfaces plus 21 files wiring Escape handlers exist. But none implement a focus trap or move initial focus into the dialog, so a keyboard/AT user's focus stays on the trigger behind the overlay; Tab walks the page underneath the modal. This affects `ConfirmModal`, `components/ui/DetailDrawer.tsx`, `app/operator/_components/HelpPanel.tsx`, `app/operator/media/_components/MediaPreview.tsx` / `CreateShareModal.tsx` / `BulkActionBar.tsx`, `app/operator/events/[id]/room/_components/RoomDashboard.tsx`, and the `EventAccessFlow` modal. Note also `BulkActionBar.tsx:180` and `HelpPanel.tsx:65` use `onClick` on a non-interactive `<div>` for backdrop/stop-propagation (acceptable as backdrop, but not keyboard-dismissable beyond Escape).
+
+The package.json already ships `@radix-ui/react-dialog ^1.1.15`, and the design tokens doc in CLAUDE.md explicitly states "Radix UI primitives (WCAG 2.2 AA)" as the intended primitive. Yet **Radix Dialog is used in zero files** — Radix appears only in `app/apply/[slug]/page.tsx` (checkbox/label). So the locked design intent (Radix for a11y) is unrealized for every modal in the app.
+
+**Fix:** Migrate the shared modal primitives (`ConfirmModal`, `DetailDrawer`, and the media/room dialogs) to `@radix-ui/react-dialog`, which gives focus trap, initial-focus, Escape, scroll-lock, and `aria-labelledby`/`aria-describedby` wiring for free — matching the CLAUDE.md "Radix UI primitives (WCAG 2.2 AA)" decision. This is one component swap that fixes every modal at once. If a full migration is out of appetite, at minimum add a focus-trap + initial-focus effect to `ConfirmModal` and `DetailDrawer` since they are the shared base.
+
+### [INFO] Many `<label>` elements are not programmatically associated with their inputs
+
+27 `htmlFor` usages against 151 `<label>` occurrences. The gap is partly labels wrapping their input (implicit association, fine) and partly decorative labels, so this is not a blanket failure — but the ratio signals that a meaningful share of form fields in the settings editors and the DAM/intelligence panels likely rely on visual proximity only, which fails WCAG 1.3.1 / 4.1.2 for screen-reader users.
+
+**Fix:** Audit the settings editors (`app/operator/settings/**/_components/*Editor.tsx`) and confirm every `<label>` either wraps its control or carries `htmlFor` matching the control's `id`. Where icon-only buttons exist, confirm `aria-label` (121 `aria-label` usages exist, which is healthy — just verify every icon-only `<button>` is covered).
+
+### [CRITICAL] ~3,200 LOC of dev/QA tooling ships in the production operator bundle on every operator page
+
+`app/operator/layout.tsx:16` statically imports `DevToolbar`, and renders `<DevToolbar workspaceId={workspaceId} />` at line 101 for every operator route. `DevToolbar.tsx` is **1,270 LOC** (`'use client'`) and statically imports `QAMissionPanel.tsx` (**1,952 LOC**, `'use client'`) at `DevToolbar.tsx:10`. Together that is ~3,222 LOC of QA-mission/persona/seed tooling.
+
+It is gated only at **runtime** by `NEXT_PUBLIC_DEV_USER_IDS` (`DevToolbar.tsx:12`) — a `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` client allowlist. That is not dead-code elimination: the import is unconditional and static, so the entire DevToolbar+QAMissionPanel JS is bundled and shipped to every operator (including production, real staff) regardless of whether they're on the allowlist. Contrast with the one place this is done right: `app/providers.tsx:14` lazy-imports react-query-devtools behind `process.env.NODE_ENV === 'development'`, which Next statically inlines so the import is tree-shaken out of prod.
+
+**Fix:** Convert the DevToolbar import in `app/operator/layout.tsx` to `next/dynamic` with `{ ssr: false }` AND guard it the same way providers.tsx does — `process.env.NODE_ENV === 'development' ? dynamic(() => import('./_components/DevToolbar')) : null` — so the ~3,200 LOC is dead-code-eliminated from the production build entirely (the runtime `NEXT_PUBLIC_DEV_USER_IDS` allowlist can stay as a secondary gate for dev). If DevToolbar must remain reachable in production for the allowlisted users, at minimum make the `QAMissionPanel` import inside DevToolbar a `next/dynamic` lazy import so the 1,952-LOC panel only loads when actually opened. This is the single largest bundle win available.
+
+### [WARNING] Near-absent code-splitting across six monolith client components
+
+Six client components exceed 1,000 LOC and are statically imported, mostly with no `next/dynamic` boundary:
+- `app/operator/_components/QAMissionPanel.tsx` — 1,952 (see CRITICAL above)
+- `app/apply/_components/MembershipForm.tsx` — 1,860 (`'use client'`, on the public `/apply` LCP path)
+- `app/operator/applications/_components/ApplicationsQueue.tsx` — 1,287 (`'use client'`)
+- `app/operator/_components/DevToolbar.tsx` — 1,270 (see CRITICAL above)
+- `app/m/events/[slug]/_components/EventAccessFlow.tsx` — 1,105 (`'use client'`, member event-detail LCP path)
+- `app/operator/events/_components/SeriesPanel.tsx` — 1,071 (`'use client'`)
+
+Across the whole `app/`+`components/` tree there are only **2** `next/dynamic` call sites — and one of them (`MembershipForm.tsx:9`, `dynamic(() => import('./FroggerGame'), { ssr: false })`) is a 607-LOC easter-egg game, not a perf-driven split. So the app ships these large client trees up-front with effectively no route- or interaction-level splitting. `MembershipForm` and `EventAccessFlow` are the most consequential because they sit on public/member LCP paths.
+
+**Fix:** Lazy-load the heavy, conditionally-shown subtrees. `EventAccessFlow` (1,105 LOC) renders inside a modal triggered by a CTA — wrap it in `next/dynamic` so the member event page hydrates without it until the user clicks "Register"/"Get Ticket". For `MembershipForm`, split the per-screen step components and the photo-upload/review steps behind dynamic boundaries so screen 1 (the LCP) ships minimal JS. `SeriesPanel` and `ApplicationsQueue` detail/editor panels are good candidates for splitting the slide-over/detail subtree from the list view.
+
+### [WARNING] No list virtualization — DAM grid and operator queues render unbounded DOM
+
+`@tanstack/react-virtual ^3.14.2` is a dependency but is used in exactly **one** file: `app/operator/members/_components/MemberTimeline.tsx`. Every other large collection renders the full array:
+- `app/operator/media/_components/MediaGrid.tsx:121` — `{assets.map((a, i) => …)}` renders every DAM asset as a `MediaTile` with a justified-layout pass (`justifiedLayout(...)` at line 49) plus per-tile FLIP transitions in a `useLayoutEffect`. The DAM is explicitly a media library seeded with demo media and intended to scale; an unvirtualized justified grid with FLIP on every tile will jank badly at a few hundred assets.
+- `app/operator/applications/_components/ApplicationsQueue.tsx` (1,287 LOC) and the operator data tables (`EventsTable`, `EventAttendeesTab`, `RsvpList`, `MediaList`) render full result sets into the DOM. 119 `.map(` call sites across the applications/events/member-events trees.
+
+**Fix:** Add `useVirtualizer` to `MediaGrid` (the highest-cardinality surface) — the justified-layout boxes already give you exact per-row geometry, so you can drive a windowed renderer off `layout.boxes` and only mount tiles whose row is in view; this also removes the cost of FLIP-measuring off-screen tiles. Apply the same to `ApplicationsQueue` and `EventAttendeesTab` once attendee/applicant counts grow, or as a stopgap paginate/`slice` the server query. You already own the library — the win is wiring, not a new dependency.
+
+### [WARNING] Zero `next/image` — every rendered image is a raw `<img>`, including on LCP paths
+
+`next/image` is imported in exactly **one** file (`app/m/pass/page.tsx:5`). All six rendered images are raw `<img>`:
+- `app/m/events/_components/EventsGrid.tsx:66` — member event-grid hero (`<img src={src} alt="" className="h-full w-full object-cover" />`). The `EventHeroImage` is the dominant visual on the member events list — a likely LCP element — and ships with no width/height (CLS risk), no `loading`/`fetchpriority`, no responsive `srcset`, and no optimization. There's even an eslint-disable comment acknowledging the raw img.
+- `app/m/events/[slug]/_components/TemplateMinimal.tsx:58` — member event-detail hero (LCP on the detail page)
+- `app/operator/events/_components/HeroImageUpload.tsx:89`, `app/operator/media/_components/UploadDropzone.tsx:297`, `MediaPreview.tsx:110`, `app/apply/_components/MembershipForm.tsx:1331`
+
+**Fix:** Convert the two member-facing hero images (`EventsGrid.tsx:66`, `TemplateMinimal.tsx:58`) to `next/image` with explicit `width`/`height` (or `fill` + sized parent), `sizes`, and `priority` on the above-the-fold detail hero — this is the direct LCP + CLS win on the member surfaces. For DAM/media previews, raw `<img>` against signed R2 URLs is defensible (the thumbnails are already server-resized via Sharp and Next's optimizer can't see private signed URLs cheaply), but pair them with explicit dimensions + `loading="lazy"` to kill layout shift. The empty `alt=""` on `EventsGrid.tsx:66` / `TemplateMinimal.tsx:58` is acceptable only if the event title is adjacent text (it is) — keep it decorative-empty rather than redundant.
+
+### [INFO] Semantic HTML is largely healthy — clickable-div anti-pattern is essentially absent
+
+Only **2** `onClick` handlers sit on non-interactive `<div>`/`<span>` elements (`HelpPanel.tsx:65`, `BulkActionBar.tsx:180`), and both are modal-backdrop / stop-propagation wrappers, not faux-buttons. Data tables use real `<table>` (`components/ui/DataTable.tsx` and 8 operator tables), the skip link is real and wired (`app/layout.tsx:101` → `#main-content`, styled at `globals.css:970`), and icon buttons are broadly `aria-label`'d (121 usages). This is a genuinely strong baseline — the a11y debt is concentrated in focus indicators and modal focus management, not in element semantics.
+
+---
+
+## What's healthy
+
+- **Global focus baseline is correct in principle:** `:focus-visible` ring + `:focus:not(:focus-visible)` reset + per-theme overrides at `globals.css:958-967` — the failure is element-level overrides defeating it, not a missing baseline.
+- **Skip-to-main link** exists and is properly visually-hidden-until-focus (`app/layout.tsx:101`, `globals.css:970-992`).
+- **Semantic HTML:** real `<table>` data tables, real `<label>`s, almost no clickable-div anti-pattern.
+- **Custom modals carry `role="dialog"` + `aria-modal` + Escape** even before any Radix migration.
+- **Theme system is token-driven** (no hex literals in the audited component classes — colors are CSS vars per the Absolute Rule), which keeps focus-ring contrast theme-aware.
+- **react-query-devtools is the model for prod stripping** (`providers.tsx:14`) — the pattern to copy for DevToolbar.
+- **Dependencies for the fixes already exist** — `@radix-ui/react-dialog`, `@tanstack/react-virtual`, and `next/image` are all installed; most fixes are wiring, not new deps (respecting CLAUDE.md "do not add dependencies as a side effect").
+
+No sponsor-firewall (`lib/intelligence/sponsor-safe.ts`) or locked-decision concerns touched by these frontend changes; all recommendations are additive/refactor-in-place and READ-ONLY findings only.
