+# QA Audit — NoBC OS — 2026-06-09
+
+**Verdict:** Test suite is healthy where it exists (21 unit files / ~173 tests, member-intelligence + sponsor firewall well covered) but has a dangerous blind spot — the entire money path (Stripe webhook, capture, refund, payment-intent) and the event-access gate logic have ZERO automated tests, and the lone E2E spec drives a real AI agent with 75s timeouts and `retries:1`, making it the single most flaky surface in CI.
+
+---
+
+### [CRITICAL] The Stripe webhook handler has zero test coverage — the entire money state machine is unguarded
+
+`app/api/webhooks/nobc/stripe/route.ts` (213 lines, re-exported by `app/api/webhooks/stripe/route.ts:2`) is the source of truth for converting payment events into seat confirmations. No test imports it (`grep -rln "webhooks/nobc/stripe" tests/` → NONE). Untested branches that directly move money/seats:
+
+- `checkout.session.completed` → sets `status: 'CONFIRMED'` (route.ts:43-46).
+- `payment_intent.amount_capturable_updated` → `paymentStatus: 'AUTHORIZED'` (route.ts:101-104).
+- `payment_intent.succeeded` → `paymentStatus: 'CAPTURED', capturedAt` (route.ts:166-169).
+- `payment_intent.payment_failed`/`canceled` → only flips RSVPs where `ticketStatus IN ['held']` (route.ts:194-197). A double-charge / partial-capture / out-of-order-webhook scenario (Stripe does not guarantee ordering) would silently leave an RSVP in the wrong state, and there is no test asserting idempotency or ordering tolerance.
+
+The handler also reads `session.metadata` with an unchecked cast (route.ts:27-29) and only guards `rsvpId`/`workspaceId`, not `memberId` — a malformed metadata payload reaches `db.member.findFirst({ where: { id: memberId } })` with `memberId === undefined`.
+
+**Fix:** Add `tests/unit/stripe-webhook.test.ts` that mocks `@/lib/stripe` (stub `webhooks.constructEvent`), `@/lib/db`, `@/lib/resend`, and `@/lib/emit-event`, then asserts each of the four `event.type` branches produces the exact `db.rSVP.update(...)` payload, that an invalid signature returns 400 (route.ts:20-22), and that a replayed `payment_intent.succeeded` is idempotent. Mirror the mocking pattern already proven in `tests/unit/member-merge.test.ts`.
+
+---
+
+### [CRITICAL] Event-access gate logic (member/guest/closed + price derivation) is pure, security-critical, and completely untested
+
+`lib/event-access.ts` decides who can access an event and how much they pay — `resolveViewer` (line 142), `resolveAccessForViewer` (line 151), `deriveFlow` (line 22), `priceForResolved` (in `event-access-submit.ts:88`). It is deterministic pure logic — ideal for unit tests — yet `grep -rn "from '@/lib/event-access'" tests/` → NONE.
+
+High-risk untested invariants:
+- A member viewing a member-disabled / guest-enabled event silently falls through to the guest gate and **guest price** (`resolveAccessForViewer`, lines 160-163). A regression here over- or under-charges members with no test to catch it.
+- `priceForResolved` only charges a `pay` step that occurs **before the first approval gate** (`inSessionFlow`, `event-access.ts:177-180`). A reordering bug would charge $0 up front for a paid event (revenue loss) or charge before approval (chargeback risk).
+- `parseEventAccess` (line 131) silently falls back to `defaultEventAccess()` on any unparseable blob (line 139) — a corrupt/legacy `eventAccess` JSON would open an event to the wrong audience with no signal. The two legacy migration maps (`LEGACY_MEMBER_GATE`/`LEGACY_GUEST_GATE`, lines 60-76) are entirely unexercised.
+
+**Fix:** Add `tests/unit/event-access.test.ts` — no mocks needed (pure functions). Cover the truth table: {member, guest, anon} × {member-only, guest-only, both-disabled, ticketed, apply-required} asserting `kind`, `priceCents`, and `flow`; plus `priceForResolved` for pay-before-gate vs pay-after-gate; plus each legacy migration map round-trips through `parseEventAccess` to a valid shape.
+
+---
+
+### [WARNING] Refund, capture, and capture-payments cron money paths are untested
+
+`app/api/stripe/refund/route.ts` (ADMIN-gated, 79 lines) branches on live Stripe PI status — `requires_capture` → cancel, `succeeded` → refund, else 400 (lines 39-47) — and writes `paymentStatus: 'REFUNDED'`. `app/api/stripe/capture/route.ts` (68 lines) and `app/api/cron/capture-payments/route.ts` (52 lines) are equally untested. The refund route's double-refund guard (`rsvp.refundedAt` → 409, line 31) is exactly the kind of guard that should have a regression test. None of these three are referenced by any test.
+
+**Fix:** Add a `tests/unit/stripe-money-routes.test.ts` mocking `@/lib/stripe`, `@/lib/db`, `@/lib/operator-role` (force `requireRole` ok), `@/lib/emit-event`. Assert: refund of an already-refunded RSVP returns 409; `requires_capture` PI calls `paymentIntents.cancel` and records `pi.amount`; `succeeded` PI calls `refunds.create`; a PI in any other status returns 400 without a DB write.
+
+---
+
+### [WARNING] The only E2E spec drives a live AI agent — high flaky-test risk in CI
+
+`tests/e2e/spotlight.spec.ts` is the entire E2E suite (one file, 3 tests). Every test types a query into the Cmd+K palette and "hands it to the agent" (spotlight.spec.ts:19), then waits on AI-produced DOM with `timeout: 75_000` (lines 30, 43, 63). `playwright.config.ts` sets `timeout: 90_000`, `retries: 1`, `workers: 1` and comments that "agent turns make several real AI round-trips." This means: (a) CI spends minutes on real Anthropic calls, (b) any model latency spike or non-deterministic agent output (e.g. failing to surface `Carter Blake`, spotlight.spec.ts:31) flakes the build, and (c) `retries: 1` masks intermittent failures rather than surfacing them. There is no deterministic/mocked-agent variant.
+
+**Fix:** Split E2E into (1) a deterministic tier that stubs the `/api/agent` response (Playwright `page.route`) so palette → record-card / record-list / metric-deeplink rendering is asserted without a live model, and (2) an opt-in `@ai` smoke tier (env-gated, excluded from the default CI run). Keep `retries: 1` only on the `@ai` tier; the deterministic tier should run with `retries: 0` so flakes are visible. Also widen E2E beyond spotlight — the access/checkout flow and operator approval have no E2E at all.
+
+---
+
+### [WARNING] Check-in PWA endpoint untested despite an offline-idempotency contract and a transactional member counter
+
+`app/api/check-in/[rsvpId]/route.ts` is explicitly designed to be "safe to call multiple times offline/online" (line 5) and runs a 3-statement `$transaction` that increments `member.totalEventsAttended` (lines 33-54). The idempotency guard (`rsvp.checkedIn` → early return, lines 27-29) and the `ticketStatus IN ['confirmed','held']` gate (line 22) are the exact behaviors an offline PWA depends on — a regression that double-increments `totalEventsAttended` on a re-sync would corrupt attendance counts feeding the intelligence layer. The `CHECKIN_SECRET` bearer check (lines 10-13) is also untested. No test references this route.
+
+**Fix:** Add `tests/unit/check-in-route.test.ts` mocking `@/lib/db` + `@/lib/engagement`: assert a fresh check-in writes all three transaction statements, a second call with `checkedIn:true` returns `{alreadyCheckedIn:true}` WITHOUT a second increment, a wrong/missing bearer returns 401, and a `ticketStatus` outside the allow-list returns 422.
+
+---
+
+### [INFO] Member identity-merge is well tested but the production query path is only asserted at the mock boundary
+
+`tests/unit/member-merge.test.ts` (175 lines, 7 tests) exercises real `executeMerge`/`findMergeCandidates` logic against mocked Prisma (good — it asserts the tombstone `mergedIntoId`, RSVP repoint vs archive, and that `memberId`/`eventId` are not leaked into update payloads). This is the strongest critical-path coverage in the suite. The remaining gap is that the merge depends on the same `mergedIntoId IS NULL` invariant the sponsor firewall view bakes in (`sponsor-firewall.test.ts:69`) — there is no test asserting a merged (tombstoned) member is excluded from the live access/RSVP creation path, only from the sponsor view.
+
+**Fix (low priority):** Add one assertion to the access-submit test suite (once it exists) that `findOrCreateGuestMember`/RSVP creation never resolves onto a `mergedIntoId != null` row.
+
+---
+
+### [INFO] Sponsor firewall gate is structurally sound — preserve it as-is
+
+`tests/unit/sponsor-firewall.test.ts` is a genuine runtime guard, not a vanity test: it source-scans 7 sponsor-facing modules for psychographic-read tokens (lines 17-44), asserts the `SponsorAudienceMember`/`ProvenanceSource` type boundary exists (lines 48-54), and asserts the SQL view is JOIN-free, `SELECT *`-free, and bakes in `mergedIntoId IS NULL` + `status = 'APPROVED'` (lines 60-75). Combined with the compile-time `_SponsorSafe` assertion in `lib/intelligence/sponsor-safe.ts:107-113`, this is structure + tests, exactly as CLAUDE.md requires. One latent risk: the `SPONSOR_FACING` array (lines 17-25) is a hand-maintained allowlist — a NEW sponsor-facing route added later would not be scanned automatically.
+
+**Fix (low priority):** Consider deriving `SPONSOR_FACING` from a glob over `app/{assets,doc,operator/intelligence/sponsor}/**` so a newly-added sponsor surface is auto-included in the scan rather than silently skipped.
+
+---
+
+## What's healthy
+
+- Member-intelligence layer (identity, provenance, merge, record routes, score display) has real, logic-exercising coverage — `member-merge.test.ts`, `member-patch-route.test.ts` (11 tests), `member-provenance.test.ts` (11 tests), `score-display.test.ts` (30 tests).
+- The sponsor firewall is the model the rest of the suite should follow: physical (separate table), typed (compile-time `Assert`), and runtime-scanned. Do not weaken it.
+- `vitest.config.ts` correctly scopes unit tests to `tests/unit/**` so they never collide with the Playwright `*.spec.ts` suite — clean separation.
+- No flaky-risk patterns (`Date.now`, `Math.random`, `setTimeout`, real sleeps) found inside the unit suite — unit tests are deterministic. Flaky risk is isolated to the AI-driven E2E tier.
+- RBAC money-path entry (`requireRole(ADMIN)` on refund, refund.ts:14-15) and the check-in bearer gate are present in code; the gap is test coverage, not the guards themselves.
