@@ -0,0 +1,79 @@
+# Reliability Audit — NoBC OS (2026-06-09)
+
+**Verdict:** Error boundaries log correctly and the firewall is untouched, but the Producer/Svix/House-Phone delivery paths have real reliability gaps — no `global-error.tsx`, no inbound-SMS idempotency (Twilio retries re-charge the AI and double-text guests), an in-memory rate limiter that resets on every Railway deploy, and zero alerting on any silent webhook/queue failure (the "queue on failure" the architecture promises does not exist in code).
+
+---
+
+### [CRITICAL] Inbound SMS has no idempotency — Twilio retries double-process and double-reply
+
+`nobc-house-phone/routes/inbound.js:65-187` persists the INBOUND `SmsMessage` (line 95) and then runs AI triage + `sendSMS` + an OUTBOUND insert (lines 171-180). Any failure *after* the inbound insert — `triage()` throwing (`lib/ai.js:57` throws on non-2xx Anthropic), `sendSMS` throwing (`lib/twilio.js:24`), or a DB hiccup — falls into the `catch` at line 183 and returns **HTTP 500**. Twilio treats a 500 as a delivery failure and **retries the same webhook** (same `MessageSid`). On retry the code:
+- inserts a **duplicate INBOUND row** (no dedup on `MessageSid` — confirmed absent: no `MessageSid`/`twilioSid` column in `prisma/schema.prisma` and no lookup in `inbound.js`),
+- re-runs the **paid Haiku call**, and
+- **sends a second SMS** to the guest if the first `sendSMS` actually succeeded before a later line threw.
+
+Even the happy path is non-atomic: the inbound insert, contact-lookup `UPDATE`s, OUTBOUND insert, and `sendSMS` are separate awaits with no transaction, so a crash mid-sequence leaves partial state that the retry compounds.
+
+**Fix:** Capture `req.body.MessageSid`, add a unique `providerSid String? @unique` to `SmsMessage`, and `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (providerSid) DO NOTHING` at the top of the handler; if the insert affected 0 rows, return `200` immediately (already processed). Wrap the inbound insert + contact updates in a transaction. Critically, **send the AI reply outside the request's failure path** — return `200` to Twilio as soon as the inbound message is durably stored, then fire triage/sendSMS; never let an Anthropic/Twilio error turn into a 500 that triggers a Twilio retry of the whole pipeline.
+
+---
+
+### [CRITICAL] "Queue on failure" does not exist — Producer + Svix deliveries are dropped silently with no alert
+
+CLAUDE.md and `lib/producer-webhook.ts:5` both describe the Phase J pattern as "Fire-and-forget, **one retry, queue on failure**." There is **no queue**. After two synchronous attempts (`producer-webhook.ts:53-54`), a permanent failure only writes an `AuditEvent` with action `producer.notify.failed` (line 60) and returns. Nothing re-drives it; nothing pages anyone. Producer silently misses the event publish/update/cancel and the two systems drift — invisible until someone manually reads the audit log.
+
+Svix delivery in `lib/emit-event.ts:65-87` is even quieter: on any throw it does `console.error` and returns (line 86). No audit row, no retry, no alert.
+
+There is also **no error-monitoring/alerting integration anywhere** — `grep` for `sentry|datadog|opentelemetry|@vercel/otel|pagerduty` across `lib/` and `app/` returns nothing; the only deps are `svix` and `twilio`. Every failure mode in this audit surfaces *only* as a `console.error` in Vercel/Railway logs that no one is watching.
+
+**Fix:** Make the audit row the durable queue: on `producer.notify.failed`, have a Vercel cron (you already run one at `vercel.json`) sweep recent `producer.notify.failed` audit rows and re-attempt, marking them delivered. For Svix, wrap the `emit-event` failure in an audit row too (`svix.delivery.failed`) so it is reconcilable — Svix's own dashboard covers per-message retry, but only for messages that were *accepted*; a throw before `message.create` means Svix never saw it. Add a real error sink (Sentry or even a Slack alert via the existing `maybeFireSlack`) for `*.failed` audit actions so silent drift becomes a notification.
+
+---
+
+### [WARNING] No `global-error.tsx` — root-layout/render crashes escape the logging boundary
+
+`app/error.tsx:12-18` correctly logs caught errors (the `baf3031` fix). But `app/error.tsx` only catches errors thrown *inside* the route segment it wraps — it cannot catch errors thrown in the **root layout** or in `error.tsx`'s own render. Next.js App Router requires a separate `app/global-error.tsx` for that, and it does **not exist** (confirmed: `ls app/global-error.tsx` → not found). A failure in the root layout (theme provider, Clerk provider, font loading) therefore renders Next's default white error page **with no `console.error`** — exactly the "silently swallow" failure mode CLAUDE.md's Debugging & observability rule prohibits, just at a layer the existing fix didn't reach.
+
+**Fix:** Add `app/global-error.tsx` (a client component that re-renders `<html><body>`) mirroring the `console.error` logging in `app/error.tsx:12-18`, so root-level crashes also surface in logs.
+
+---
+
+### [WARNING] In-memory SMS rate limiter resets on every Railway deploy/restart and is per-instance
+
+`nobc-house-phone/routes/inbound.js:15-31` implements per-phone rate limiting in a module-level `Map`. CLAUDE.md cites "per-phone rate limiting" as a *reason* Runtype was scratched in favor of this service, so it is load-bearing. But the `Map` is process-local: it is **wiped on every deploy, crash, or restart**, and if Railway ever runs more than one instance the limit is per-instance (N× the intended ceiling). An abuser who triggers a redeploy — or just hits a cold start — gets a fresh 10-message budget. There is also no cap on the number of distinct phones tracked, so the `Map` grows unbounded (a slow memory leak; entries are never evicted, only overwritten when the same phone returns).
+
+**Fix:** Back the limiter with the shared Postgres (a small `SELECT count(*) FROM "SmsMessage" ... WHERE direction='INBOUND' AND createdAt > now() - interval '1 hour'` joined through the conversation's phone is already cheap and durable across restarts), or a Redis token bucket. At minimum, evict stale `Map` entries on a timer to bound memory.
+
+---
+
+### [WARNING] `categorize` route has an unguarded `generateObject` — a model/parse failure 500s the Intelligence tab
+
+`app/api/sms/categorize/route.ts:88-93` calls `generateObject(...)` with **no try/catch**. The route already degrades gracefully when `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` is unset (line 79-82), which signals intent to fail soft — but a transient Anthropic error, a rate limit, or a schema-validation failure (Haiku returning an out-of-enum category) throws uncaught and returns a 500 to the Intelligence dashboard, blanking the tab on load rather than degrading. Unlike the SMS reply path (`app/api/sms/reply/route.ts:40-45`, which catches Twilio and returns a clean 502), this AI call is unprotected.
+
+**Fix:** Wrap `generateObject` in try/catch and return `{ categorized: 0, remaining: remainingBefore, skipped: true }` on failure (matching the existing no-key branch), with a `console.error` so the failure is still logged.
+
+---
+
+### [INFO] Railway service's `routes/reply.js` is dead/duplicate code — a maintenance and signing-boundary hazard
+
+The operator UI sends replies via `POST /api/sms/reply` in **nobc-os** (`app/operator/house-phone/HousePhoneClient.tsx:105`), which calls Twilio directly through `lib/twilio.ts`. The Railway service also ships a `POST /sms/reply` (`nobc-house-phone/routes/reply.js`) that does the same thing — but nothing calls it (no `house-phone`/Railway URL reference in nobc-os). It is unauthenticated (no Twilio signature, no Clerk session — only the inbound route validates signatures) and, if ever exposed/wired, would be an open SMS-send endpoint against the workspace's Twilio number. It also duplicates the OUTBOUND-insert logic, so the two paths can drift.
+
+**Fix:** Delete `nobc-house-phone/routes/reply.js` and its mount (`index.js:21`). Outbound is owned by nobc-os by design (CLAUDE.md architecture); the Railway service should be inbound-only.
+
+---
+
+### [INFO] No health monitoring on the standalone Railway service
+
+`nobc-house-phone/index.js:18` exposes `GET /health` but nothing polls it. The DB pool is lazy and boots even with `DATABASE_URL` unset (`lib/db.js:5-8`), so a misconfigured deploy starts "healthy," accepts Twilio webhooks, and fails only at the first query inside the `try` — returning 500s that trigger Twilio retries (see CRITICAL #1). Because this service is outside Vercel, it is also outside whatever Vercel-side observability exists.
+
+**Fix:** Add an uptime check (Railway healthcheck or external monitor) against `/health`, and have `/health` actually run a `SELECT 1` so a broken `DATABASE_URL` surfaces as unhealthy instead of as silent per-message 500s.
+
+---
+
+## What's healthy
+
+- **The error-boundary logging fix is real and intact.** `app/error.tsx:12-18` logs `message`, `digest`, and `stack` — the `baf3031` fix holds.
+- **`emitEvent` ordering is correct and well-reasoned.** The `AuditEvent` write is unconditional and first; the CRM engagement dual-write and Svix delivery are explicitly isolated so neither can break the compliance record (`lib/emit-event.ts:31-47`). Comments in the file accurately describe the isolation.
+- **Webhook signature verification is sound.** Producer (`app/api/webhooks/producer/route.ts:21-29`) and Stripe (`app/api/webhooks/nobc/stripe/route.ts:18-22`) both verify signatures with `timingSafeEqual` / `constructEvent` and fail closed; the Twilio inbound validator (`nobc-house-phone/lib/twilio.js:34-56`) uses `timingSafeEqual` with a length guard.
+- **Stripe webhook fan-out side effects are correctly fire-and-forget with logging** — every `emitEvent(...)` and `resend.emails.send(...)` carries a `.catch(err => console.error(...))` so a Svix/email failure never blocks the payment state update (`app/api/webhooks/nobc/stripe/route.ts:59-66, 117-124, 199-206`).
+- **The sponsor firewall is untouched** — this audit was read-only; `lib/intelligence/sponsor-safe.ts` and `tests/unit/sponsor-firewall.test.ts` were not modified, and no audited path crosses the sponsor boundary.
+- **The prompt-injection hardening on the House Phone AI is in place** — `nobc-house-phone/lib/ai.js:8-17` instructs the model to treat patron messages as untrusted data and never adopt a persona, with the message wrapped accordingly at line 49.
