+# NoBC OS — Security Audit (2026-06-09)
+
+**Verdict:** Strong overall posture — REST `/api/operator/*` write RBAC is comprehensive, the sponsor firewall is structurally sound (type + view + test), secrets are gitignored, raw SQL is parameterized, and signed webhooks verify correctly — but the `/api/mcp` Bearer write path lets any authenticated org member (even a READ_ONLY-floor member) execute STAFF/ADMIN-equivalent mutations with no role check, which is a CRITICAL privilege-escalation gap that bypasses the entire `requireRole` boundary.
+
+---
+
+### [CRITICAL] `/api/mcp` write path performs no role check — any authenticated org member can run destructive mutations
+
+`app/api/mcp/route.ts:26-54` authenticates via `authenticateMcp` (`lib/mcp/auth.ts:21-32`), which resolves only `{ userId, workspaceId }` — see `McpContext` in `lib/mcp/types.ts:8-11`. There is no `OperatorRole` on the context and no `requireRole`/`isStaff`/`isAdmin` call anywhere in the MCP dispatch chain (`lib/mcp/server.ts`, `lib/mcp/registry.ts:57-66`). The registered tools include destructive writes: `events.ts` (`db.event.create/update`), `applications.ts` (approve → `db.application.update` + `db.member.upsert`), `rsvps.ts` (`db.rSVP.update`), and `members.ts` (`db.member.update`). The Bearer path (`userIdFromBearer`, `lib/mcp/auth.ts:34-51`) accepts ANY valid Clerk session token, and the session fallback (`userIdFromSession`) accepts any logged-in browser session. Because `requireRole` applies a READ_ONLY floor to plain Clerk org members, a member who is intentionally view-only in the REST UI can mint a Clerk session token, POST `tools/call` to `/api/mcp`, and approve applications / create / edit / cancel events / mutate members — the exact operations the REST routes gate behind STAFF/ADMIN. This is privilege escalation and a divergence from the audited REST coverage. CLAUDE.md acknowledges the gate is "ungated... needs its own design," but the surface is live and reachable today.
+
+**Fix:** Gate every mutating MCP tool by effective role before execution. Add a `minRole` to the `McpTool` type, populate `McpContext` with the caller's `getEffectiveRole(userId, workspaceId)` inside `authenticateMcp`, and in `callTool` (or `handleOne` `tools/call`) reject with a JSON-RPC error when `roleAtLeast(ctx.role, tool.minRole)` is false — STAFF for the operational writes, ADMIN for sensitive ones, mirroring the REST table. Until that lands, restrict the route at the edge (e.g. only allow it for an explicit operator allowlist / deny the session-cookie fallback for write methods), or disable `tools/call` for non-`list`/`read` tools.
+
+### [WARNING] Single global `CHECKIN_SECRET` is a cross-tenant bearer with no workspace scoping on `/api/check-in/[rsvpId]`
+
+`app/api/check-in/[rsvpId]/route.ts:10-21` authorizes on a plain string-equality bearer (`CHECKIN_SECRET`) and then looks up the RSVP by id alone (`db.rSVP.findUnique({ where: { id: rsvpId } })`) with no `workspaceId` constraint. The same secret is the single value for the whole deployment, and it is shipped to the browser as `NEXT_PUBLIC_CHECKIN_SECRET` (`app/check-in/[slug]/_components/CheckInClient.tsx:9`, `WalkinModal.tsx:6`, `EventCheckinTab.tsx:24`) — i.e. it is world-readable in the client bundle by design. In single-tenant (NoBC) operation this is acceptable, but as a multi-tenant SaaS (Tenant Zero model, per CLAUDE.md) one tenant's door-scanner secret equals every tenant's: anyone holding it can check in (`/[rsvpId]`) or enumerate guest lists for any other workspace's event. `/api/check-in/event` and `/api/check-in/walkin` are correctly workspace-scoped by slug, but `[rsvpId]` is not.
+
+**Fix:** Make the check-in secret per-workspace (store a `checkinSecret` on `Workspace`, resolve the workspace from the scan context, and compare per-tenant), and add `workspaceId` to the `[rsvpId]` lookup so a check-in can only mutate an RSVP in the secret's own workspace. Use `crypto.timingSafeEqual` for the comparison rather than `===` to remove the timing side-channel on the token.
+
+### [WARNING] Producer webhook trusts `data.workspaceId` from the body and skips the ownership check on the upsert path
+
+`app/api/webhooks/producer/route.ts:63-101` upserts an `Event` keyed on `producerEventId`, writing whatever `data.workspaceId` the (HMAC-signed) payload carries — and on the `event.published`/`event.updated` path there is no check that an existing row's `workspaceId` matches the incoming one, unlike the `event.cancelled` branch which explicitly 403s on `event.workspaceId !== data.workspaceId` (lines 112-114). The signature (`verifySignature`, lines 21-29) is correct (HMAC-SHA256 + `timingSafeEqual` guarded by try/catch for length mismatch), so this is only exploitable by a compromised/buggy Producer or shared-secret leak — but since Producer and NoBC share the same Postgres instance, a mistaken or malicious `workspaceId` on a `producerEventId` collision silently re-homes an event across tenants.
+
+**Fix:** On the upsert path, mirror the cancel path: when an `Event` with that `producerEventId` already exists, refuse (or ignore) the write if its stored `workspaceId` differs from `data.workspaceId`, so `producerEventId` cannot move a row between workspaces.
+
+### [INFO] Operator-configured outbound webhook is an unrestricted server-side fetch (stored SSRF surface)
+
+`lib/comments-notify.ts:90-114` POSTs notification payloads to a URL read from a workspace setting (`webhookSetting.value`). Writing that setting is ADMIN-gated (`/api/operator/settings/*` → `requireRole(ADMIN)`), so the blast radius is limited to an admin of the same tenant, but the fetch has no scheme/host allowlist and no block on internal/metadata addresses — a malicious or compromised admin could point it at `http://169.254.169.254/...` or internal services and use the server as a request proxy/probe.
+
+**Fix:** Validate the configured webhook URL on write (require `https://`, reject private/link-local/loopback ranges and metadata IPs), or constrain it to known providers (Slack/Discord host allowlist). Apply the same guard to any other tenant-configurable outbound URL (e.g. `PRODUCER_WEBHOOK_URL` if ever made user-settable).
+
+### [INFO] MCP session-cookie fallback widens the write surface beyond intended Bearer clients
+
+`lib/mcp/auth.ts:22` falls back to `userIdFromSession()` (an active Clerk browser session) when no Bearer token is present. This is convenient for in-app/Claude-Desktop callers but means the MCP endpoint is also reachable via ordinary cookies from a logged-in browser, broadening the attack surface for the CRITICAL above (CSRF-style POSTs are mitigated by the JSON-RPC content type and same-origin defaults, but the path still bypasses `requireRole`).
+
+**Fix:** Once MCP role-gating lands (CRITICAL), keep the session fallback read-only — or require the Bearer path for any `tools/call` that hits a destructive tool.
+
+---
+
+## What's healthy
+
+- **REST `/api/operator/*` write RBAC is comprehensive and correct.** Every mutating route (`POST`/`PATCH`/`PUT`/`DELETE`) calls `requireRole` with the right floor: STAFF for operational writes (applications approve/reject/hold/waitlist, events CRUD + comp + promote-waitlist + bulk-delete, rsvps approve/cancel/reject, tiers, series, comments, lists, notifications, members/create) and ADMIN for sensitive ones (`settings/*`, `team/*`, `members/bulk`, `rsvps/[id]/refund`). GET/read routes are intentionally open to any resolved member. `requireRole` (`lib/operator-role.ts:130-144`) resolves the effective role server-side and returns clean 401/403 — UI hiding is correctly treated as cosmetic only.
+- **Sponsor firewall is structurally enforced, not convention.** `lib/intelligence/sponsor-safe.ts` projects to an explicit firmographic/coarse-demographic field list and has a compile-time `_SponsorSafe` assertion that breaks the build if a psychographic key is ever added. `tests/unit/sponsor-firewall.test.ts` is the runtime gate: it source-scans the sponsor-facing surfaces for psychographic reads AND asserts the `sponsor_audience_member` view has no JOIN, no `SELECT *`, and bakes in the `mergedIntoId IS NULL` / `status = 'APPROVED'` invariants.
+- **Secrets handling.** `.env*`, `.claude/`, `*.pem`, and the standalone `nobc-house-phone/` repo are gitignored; `git ls-files` shows no tracked env files; no live secrets are committed in `app/`/`lib/` (only `process.env.*` references and a `sk_test_` prefix check). The share-auth cookie keys its HMAC on the per-ShareLink stored password hash, so a leaked cookie can't forge any other share.
+- **Injection.** The only raw SQL (`app/api/media/dam/assets/route.ts:38`) uses `Prisma.sql` with parameterized fragments; sort is a fixed `ASSET_SORTS` map indexed by a validated key; FTS user input flows through Prisma `contains` (parameterized). No `$queryRawUnsafe`/`$executeRawUnsafe` anywhere.
+- **Signed/secret boundaries verify correctly.** Stripe webhook uses `stripe.webhooks.constructEvent`; Producer webhook HMAC uses `timingSafeEqual` (length-guarded); share-auth and share-resolve enforce expiry, revoke, password gate, and download cap (`lib/share/resolve.ts:81`, `app/assets/[token]/page.tsx`). Dev routes are gated by `NODE_ENV !== 'development'` or a `DEV_USER_IDS` allowlist.
+- **No SSRF in the AI/DAM fetch paths.** Server-side `fetch` calls in `lib/intelligence/deliverables.ts` and the DAM tagging paths target internally-presigned R2 URLs, not user-supplied URLs.
+- **Dependencies** (`package.json`) are current and reputable (Next 15.5.18, Prisma 7.8, Clerk 7, Stripe 22, Zod 4) with no obviously abandoned or typosquat packages; no high-risk transitive red flags surfaced in the lockfile review. (A live `npm audit` was out of scope under the read-only constraint — recommend running it in CI.)
